text: Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy Type 1A, also known as Unverricht-Lundborg Syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It has a material basis in the inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CSTB gene located on chromosome 21q22.3. The condition is characterized by progressive myoclonus (involuntary muscle jerks) and epilepsy, with a strong genetic component to its development. It has an exact synonym of EPM1A.

Short Syndrome, also known as Aarskog-Ose-Pande syndrome or Rieger anomaly-diabetes syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by short stature, hyperextensibility of joints, ocular depression, and other physical abnormalities. It has a material basis in mutations in the PIK3R1 gene on chromosome 5q13. The syndrome also includes mild intrauterine growth restriction, partial lipodystrophy, delayed bone age, hernias, and progeroid appearance. It is important to note that while there are several synonyms for Short Syndrome, including Lipodystrophy-Rieger anomaly-diabetes syndrome, Rieger anomaly-partial lipodystrophy syndrome, short stature, hyperextensibility, hernia, ocular depression, and teething delay, the most widely accepted term is Short Syndrome.

Gracile syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects an infant's growth and development. It is caused by mutations in the BCS1L gene on chromosome 2q35, which can lead to fetal growth restriction, aminoaciduria, cholestasis, iron overload, lactocidosis, and early death. The condition has been referred to as FLNMS, Fellman disease, Finnish lactic acidosis with hepatic hemosiderosis, Finnish lethal neonatal metabolic syndrome, growth delay-aminoaciduria-cholestasis-iron overload-lactic acidosis-early death syndrome, and growth restriction-aminoaciduria-cholestasis-iron overload-lactic acidosis-early death syndrome. It is important to note that there may be other synonyms for the condition as well.

Kaufman Oculocerebrofacial Syndrome (KOS) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that presents with developmental delay, growth retardation, low cholesterol levels, and facial dysmorphisms. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the UBE3B gene on chromosome 12q24.11. KOS has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has been identified as a syndromic intellectual disability.

Galactose epimerase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease where a mutation in the GALE gene on chromosome 1p36.1 results in a lack of galactose epimerase enzyme, which is essential for the metabolism of galactose in the body. This leads to an accumulation of galactose in the blood and other tissues, causing various symptoms such as jaundice, lethargy, developmental delay, and increased risk of infections. Galactose epimerase deficiency is also known by several other names, including GALE deficiency, GALE-D, UDP-galactose-4-epimerase deficiency, epimerase deficiency galactosemia, galactosemia III, and galactosemia type 3.

Classic galactosemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that results from mutations in the GALT gene on chromosome 9p13.3. It is characterized by a deficiency in the enzyme galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase, which leads to an accumulation of galactose in the body. This can cause several symptoms, including jaundice, lethargy, and poor feeding. Classic galactosemia is also sometimes referred to as galactosemia type 1.

combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 16 is a genetic disorder that affects the cells in the body, specifically the muscles and the heart. This leads to the accumulation of lactic acid, causing muscle weakness and fatigue. The disorder is usually inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. The genetic mutation responsible for this disorder lies on chromosome 2q36.1 and affects the MRPL44 gene. It can cause serious complications in infants, including heart failure and respiratory distress, which can be life-threatening. However, with proper medical care, it can be managed to improve symptoms and prolong life.

combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 10 (COXPD10) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the mitochondria in the body, specifically in the heart muscle and skeletal muscles. It causes hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and lactic acidosis, which are life-threatening conditions if left untreated. The disease is caused by a mutation in the MTO1 gene on chromosome 6q13. This genetic defect interferes with the normal function of the mitochondria, leading to the accumulation of harmful substances and eventually causing cell damage and failure. Infants who inherit this defect from both parents are at the highest risk for developing severe symptoms, but it can also affect individuals who have inherited the defect from only one parent. Treatment options include medication, dietary changes, and in some cases, a heart transplant may be necessary to prevent further damage.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 2 (COXPD2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce energy. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is inherited from both parents and can cause severe health problems if both copies of the gene are affected.

COXPD2 occurs due to mutations in the MRPS16 gene on chromosome 10q22.2. These mutations disrupt the function of mitochondria, which are small structures within cells that produce energy. As a result, the body is unable to produce enough energy, leading to a range of symptoms and health problems.

Some common signs and symptoms of COXPD2 include developmental delays, intellectual disability, seizures, and lactic acidosis. Lactic acidosis occurs when there is an excessive buildup of lactic acid in the bloodstream, which can be life-threatening if not treated promptly.

There is currently no cure for COXPD2, but treatment options are available to help manage symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include medications, nutritional therapy, physical therapy, speech therapy, and other specialized interventions. It is important for individuals with COXPD2 to work closely with their healthcare team to develop an individualized treatment plan that meets their specific needs.

That is correct! Li Fraumeni Syndrome 1, also known as LFS1, is a type of Li Fraumeni Syndrome characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the TP53 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. This condition can lead to various types of cancer and is often inherited in families with a history of multiple cancers.

Li Fraumeni Syndrome (LFS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organs and tissues in the body. It is characterized by the presence of two or more malignant tumors, especially in children, and a strong family history of cancer. LFS is caused by mutations in one of several tumor suppressor genes, including TP53, CHEK2, and ATM.
LFS can affect different parts of the body, such as the bones, brain, adrenal glands, and soft tissues. Some common types of cancer that are more likely to occur in people with LFS include breast, ovarian, thyroid, lung, and adrenal gland tumors.
Early detection and treatment of LFS are important to reduce the risk of developing multiple tumors and improve overall health outcomes. Genetic counseling and testing can help identify individuals who may be at risk for LFS. Treatment options depend on the specific type of cancer and its location, but may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these treatments.
In conclusion, Li Fraumeni Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that increases the risk of developing multiple types of cancer. Early detection and treatment are crucial for improving health outcomes in those affected by this condition.

Lenz-Majewski syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the growth and development of bones. It is caused by mutations in the PTDSS1 gene on chromosome 8q22.1. The condition is characterized by intellectual disability, sclerosing bone dysplasia, distinct craniofacial, dental, cutaneous and distal-limb anomalies. torrance type platyspondylic dysplasia is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal bone development, particularly in the skull and spine. It often results in short stature, bone deformities, and other health issues. Treatment typically focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. There is no cure for this condition.

Lymphedema distichiasis syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the lymphatic system and eyelashes. It is characterized by swelling in the limbs, double rows of eyelashes, and an increased risk of developing cancer. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the gene can be passed on to offspring. The FOXC2 gene on chromosome 16q24.1 is responsible for this disorder. It also has synonyms like LPHDST and lymphedema with distichiasis.

Marshall Syndrome is a type of ectodermal dysplasia that affects the development of certain bones and tissues in the skull, as well as vision, hearing, and the spine. It is caused by mutations in the COL11A1 gene on chromosome 1p21.1. The condition can lead to hypoplasia of the maxilla, nasal bones, and frontal sinuses, calvarial thickening, myopia, early-onset cataracts, and sensorineural hearing loss. It is sometimes referred to as deafness, myopia, cataract, saddle nose-Marshall type due to the characteristic facial features it presents in some cases.

melanoma and neural system tumor syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that can be caused by genetic mutations. It is characterized by a predisposition to develop cutaneous melanoma, which is a type of skin cancer, and astrocytoma, which is a type of brain tumor. The syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CDKN2A gene on chromosome 9p21.3. This condition can be inherited from one or both parents, and it increases the risk of developing these types of cancer throughout one's lifetime.

Metachondromatosis is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that occurs due to mutations in the PTPN11 gene on chromosome 12q24. It is characterized by the presence of multiple enchondromas and exostoses, which are both benign bone tumors that can cause pain and swelling. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person who has one copy of the mutated gene has a 50% chance of developing the disease. It is also known as METCDS.

Metaphyseal dysplasia, maxillary hypoplasia, brachydactyly syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the body. It is characterized by enlarged medial halves of the clavicles, metaphyseal flaring of long bones, maxillary hypoplasia, variable brachydactyly, and dystrophic teeth. The syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous duplication of the RUNX2 gene on chromosome 6p21.1.

Metatropic dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the development of bones and joints in the body. It is characterized by short limbs, limitation and enlargement of joints, severe kyphoscoliosis, platyspondyly, and metaphyseal enlargement. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. It is also known as metatropic dwarfism.

autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial dna deletions 4, also known as PEOB4, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscles responsible for eye movement. It has been linked to mutations in the DGUOK gene on chromosome 2p13.1 and is characterized by adult-onset weakness in the eye muscles and proximal limb muscles. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DGUOK gene. There are no known cures for this disease, but treatment options may include medications to manage symptoms and physical therapy to improve strength and mobility.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles that control eye movement. It is characterized by progressive weakness and wasting of these muscles, which can lead to difficulties in eye movements such as blinking, rotating the eyes, and looking up or down.

This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person only needs to inherit one copy of the gene for it to be expressed. Mitochondrial DNA deletions are seen in some cases of this disease, but the exact cause is not fully understood.

There is no cure for autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 2, but treatment options may include physical therapy to help maintain muscle strength and eye movement, medications to alleviate symptoms such as muscle spasms or pain, and support from a team of healthcare professionals.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial dna deletions 5, also known as PEOA5, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles responsible for eye movement. It is characterized by chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, which is the gradual weakening and paralysis of these muscles.

PEOA5 has a genetic basis, specifically in heterozygous mutation in the RRM2B gene on chromosome 8q22.3. This means that one copy of the gene is mutated, leading to the development of the disease. The condition also has mitochondrial DNA deletions, which can contribute to the symptoms.

It is important to note that PEOA5 has an exact synonym, autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 5, and it is also known as chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia. With proper medical care, the progression of this disease can be slowed down, but there is no cure at present.
Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial dna deletions 6 is a type of chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles and the eyes. It is characterized by progressive weakness and deterioration in the ability to move the eyes, which can lead to blindness if left untreated. The condition is caused by mutations in the TWNK gene on chromosome 10q24.31. It has an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, meaning that a person with one copy of the mutated gene has a 50% chance of passing it on to their offspring. The condition is also sometimes referred to by its synonym PEOA3.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 1, or PEOA1, is a type of chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the POLG gene on chromosome 15q26.1. It is an autosomal dominant disease, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the disease. PEOA1 is characterized by progressive weakness and paralysis of the muscles that control eye movements, leading to vision problems. It typically begins in childhood or adolescence and worsens over time. There is no cure for PEOA1, but treatment may include medications to improve eye movement and physical therapy to help maintain muscle strength and flexibility.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscles and nerves in the eyes. It is also known as chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, which causes weakness or paralysis in the eye muscles, leading to problems with eye movement. This condition is caused by mutations in the POLG gene on chromosome 15q26.1. The exact synonym for this condition is PEOB1.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial dna deletions 3 (PEOB3) is a chronic, progressive form of the disease that affects the eyes and muscles used for eye movements. It's caused by mutations in the TK2 gene on chromosome 16q21. The condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, which is weakness or paralysis of the muscles responsible for eye movement. The disease has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and is often caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TOP3A gene on chromosome 17p11.2. Spinal muscular atrophy with progressive myoclonic epilepsy (SMA-PME) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the motor neurons, resulting in severe and progressive myoclonic epilepsy and lower-motor-neuron disease. The exact synonyms for SMA-PME include Jankovic-Rivera syndrome, SMA-PME, SMAPME and hereditary myoclonus-progressive distal muscular atrophy syndrome.

Naegeli-Franceschetti-Jadassohn syndrome (NFJ) is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the skin and teeth. It is characterized by reticulate hyperpigmentation, palmoplantar keratoderma, absence of dermatoglyphics, abnormal sweat function, and dental anomalies. The condition has a strong genetic component, with most cases being inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. It is also known as Naegeli's syndrome or NFJ syndrome.

Familial multiple nevi flammei is a type of capillary disease characterized by dark red to purple, non-elevated, sharply circumscribed patches which blanch on pressure with a glass, do not spontaneously regress, and have normal rates of endothelial cell turnover. It has exact synonyms such as CMC, congenital capillary malformations, and familial multiple port-wine stains.

text:
Linear nevus sebaceous syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin, eyes, and skeletal system. It is characterized by the presence of multiple sebaceous gland tumors on the face and other parts of the body. The condition can also be associated with abnormalities in the central nervous system, eye defects, and skeletal deformities.

The syndrome is caused by somatic mosaic mutations in the NRAS, HRAS, or KRAS genes on chromosomes 1p13.2, 11p15.5, or 12p12.1, respectively. It has exact synonyms such as JNP, Jadassohn nevus phakomatosis, SFM syndrome, Schimmelpenning Feuerstein Mims syndrome, Schimmelpenning syndrome, Solomon syndrome, nevus sebaceus of Jadassohn, and nevus sebaceus syndrome. It can also be referred to as organoid nevus phakomatosis or organoid nevus syndrome.

It's important to note that Linear nevus sebaceous syndrome is a rare genetic disorder and its diagnosis should only be made by experts in genetic and medical fields. If you suspect that you or someone you know may have this condition, it is essential to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and management.

bilateral optic nerve hypoplasia is a type of bilateral optic nerve disease, which is a condition where both optic nerves are affected. It can be passed down through families and has a genetic component. The exact cause of the condition is not always known, but it may involve abnormal development of the optic nerves during fetal development.

Osteoglophonic dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by rhizomelic dwarfism, craniosynostosis, prominent supraorbital ridge, depressed nasal bridge, nonossifying bone lesions, and multiple unerupted teeth that have a material basis in heterozygous missense mutation in the FGFR1 gene on chromosome 8p11.23. It is also known as Fairbank-Keats syndrome and OGD.

Levin syndrome 2, also known as gnathodiaphyseal dysplasia, is a genetic disorder that affects bone development. It is an autosomal dominant condition, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the condition.

People with Levin syndrome 2 may experience a range of skeletal problems, including cemento-ossifying lesions in the jawbones, bone fragility, bowing or thickening of tubular bones, and sclerosis of long bones. These issues can lead to pain, deformities, and reduced mobility.

The condition is caused by a mutation in the ANO5 gene on chromosome 11p14.3. Treatment typically involves managing symptoms with medications or surgery when necessary. Early diagnosis and treatment are important to prevent complications and improve quality of life for those affected by Levin syndrome 2.

Multicentric carpotarsal osteolysis syndrome (MCTO) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by progressive loss of bone, typically involving the carpal and tarsal bones. It often leads to chronic renal failure. The exact cause of MCTO is unknown, but it has been suggested that genetic factors may play a role in its development. Some studies have identified mutations in the MAFB gene on chromosome 20q12 as a possible cause of MCTO.

progressive osseous heteroplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
progressive osseous heteroplasia is a type of syndrome.
progressive osseous heteroplasia is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
progressive osseous heteroplasia is characterized by infantile onset of dermal ossification followed by progressive bone formation in skeletal muscle and deep fascia that has_material_basis_in heterozygous loss of function mutation in the Gs-alpha isoform of the GNAS gene on chromosome 20q13.32..
progressive osseous heteroplasia has exact synonym POH.
progressive osseous heteroplasia has exact synonym ectopic ossification familial type.
progressive osseous heteroplasia has exact synonym familial ectopic ossification.
progressive osseous heteroplasia has exact synonym osteoma cutis.<|endoftext|>

Buschke-Ollendorff syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by multiple subcutaneous nevi or nodules and osteopoikilosis. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the LEMD3 gene on chromosome 12q14.3. The exact synonyms for this syndrome include dermatofibrosis lenticularis disseminata with osteopoikilosis, dermatoosteopoikilosis, disseminated dermatofibros

Paroxysmal extreme pain disorder (PEPD) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the autonomic nervous system. It is characterized by onset in the neonatal period or infancy and involves paroxysms of rectal, ocular, or submandibular pain with flushing. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SCN9A gene on chromosome 2q24.3. PEPD is also known as familial rectal pain and can be synonymous with other terms such as paroxysmal extreme pain disorder, submandibular, ocular and rectal pain with flushing, and PEXPD.

Paramyotonia congenita of Von Eulenburg (PMC) is a type of neuromuscular disease that affects infants and young children, characterized by intermittent muscle weakness and myotonia that worsens with cold exposure. It is caused by mutations in the SCN4A gene on chromosome 17q23.3 and has an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. The exact synonyms for PMC include Eulenburg disease, myotonia congenita intermittens, paralysis periodica paramyotonica, and simply paramyotonia congenita.

Parastremmatic dwarfism is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that affects the growth and development of bones and joints. It is characterized by severe dwarfism, kyphoscoliosis, stiffness of large joints, and bowing and twisting of the lower limbs. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.1.

Prolidase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the body's ability to break down certain proteins. This can lead to symptoms such as chronic and slowly healing ulcerations, recurrent infections, dysmorphic facial features, variable cognitive impairment, splenomegaly, and lack of or reduced prolidase activity. It is caused by mutations in the PEPD gene on chromosome 19q13.11. The condition is also known as hyperimidodipeptiduria, imidodipeptidase deficiency, and peptidase deficiency.

Pigmented paravenous chorioretinal atrophy (PPCA) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the eyes. It is characterized by the presence of bone corpuscle pigmentation in a paravenous distribution in the ocular fundus, which has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the CRB1 gene on chromosome 1q31.3. The exact synonym for PPCA is "pigmented para-venous chorioretinal atrophy."

familial expansile osteolysis is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
familial expansile osteolysis is a bone remodeling disease with material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance, characterized by increased bone remodeling with osteolytic lesions mainly affecting the appendicular skeleton, bone pain, pathological fractures, childhood onset of conductive hearing loss, and premature tooth loss. It has a synonym FEO and McCabe disease, but it is also known as hereditary expansile polyostotic osteolytic dysplasia.
The Juvenile Polyposis Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia Syndrome (JP-HHT) is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Guttmacher syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of limbs and genitourinary tract. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that one copy of the gene is enough to cause the disorder. The condition is characterized by preaxial deficiencies of the hands and feet, postaxial polydactyly of the hands, and hypospadias. Guttmacher syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the HOXA13 gene on chromosome 7p15.2. It is also known as autosomal dominant preaxial deficiency, postaxial polydactyly, and hypospadias syndrome.

Familial male limited precocious puberty is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the endocrine system. It is characterized by onset in early childhood of accelerated growth, early development of secondary sexual characteristics, and reduced adult height in males only. This condition has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the LHCGR gene on chromosome 2p16.3. The exact synonyms for this disease include FMPP, familial gonadotropin-independent male-limited sexual precocity, male-limited precocious puberty, and testotoxicosis.

Currarino Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the lower half of the body. It is characterized by anorectal malformations, a presacral mass (a mass in the lower back), and partial sacral agenesis (the absence of part of the sacrum). The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has an 87% chance of passing the gene for Currarino Syndrome to their children if one parent carries the gene. It is also known as Currarino Triad.
Retinal arterial tortuosity is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Ring dermoid of cornea (RDC) is a type of corneal disease characterized by the presence of annular limbal dermoids with corneal and conjunctival extension. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the PITX2 gene on chromosome 4q25. The condition can cause symptoms such as corneal opacity, visual disturbances, and pain. RDC is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person with one copy of the mutated gene has a 50% chance of developing the disease, and their offspring have a 2-3% risk. It has exact synonyms as Ring dermoid syndrome (RDS).

Aplasia of the lacrimal and salivary glands, also known as ALSG, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of these glands. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the faulty gene is enough to cause the condition.
Aplasia refers to underdevelopment or failure of development of the affected glands. In this case, the lacrimal and salivary glands may be missing or undersized. This can lead to problems such as dry eyes, difficulty swallowing, and a decreased ability to produce saliva. Some individuals with ALSG may also experience other symptoms, including cleft lip and palate, dental issues, hearing loss, and intellectual disability.
Unfortunately, there is no cure for Aplasia of the lacrimal and salivary glands at this time. However, treatments are available to help manage its symptoms. For example, individuals with dry eyes can use eye drops or other lubricating products to help keep their eyes moist. Additionally, a diet rich in saliva-producing foods, such as carrots and apples, can also be helpful. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct anatomical abnormalities or remove excess tissue from the affected glands.

Scalp, ear, nipple syndrome (SENS) is a rare autosomal dominant disorder characterized by cutis aplasia of the scalp, breast anomalies such as hypothelia or athelia, and minor anomalies of the external ears. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KCTD1 gene on chromosome 18q11.2. The exact synonyms for SENS include Finlay-Marks syndrome, Sen Syndrome, and hereditary syndrome of lumpy scalp, odd ears, and rudimentary nipples.

Neurogenic scapuloperoneal syndrome (Kaeser type) is a rare autosomal dominant disorder characterized by muscle weakness in the shoulder girdle, scapula, and the peroneal region. It has been named after its discoverers, Kaeser and Stark. This condition often presents with symptoms such as foot dorsiflexor weakness, peroneal muscle weakness, scapuloperoneal weakness, and atrophy of shoulder girdle muscles. The syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the DES gene on chromosome 2q35. It is also known as Kaeser syndrome or Stark-Kaeser syndrome.

Scapuloperoneal spinal muscular atrophy (SPMSA) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the motor neurons, leading to progressive scapuloperoneal atrophy and weakness. It can also cause laryngeal palsy, congenital absence of muscles, and in some cases, developmental abnormalities of the bones. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11.<|end|>

That is correct, spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Maroteaux type, also known as SED, is a form of autosomal dominant osteochondrodysplasia characterized by short stature, short neck, short and stubby hands and feet, platyspondyly, severe brachydactyly, and pelvic abnormalities. It has material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.1. Other synonyms for this condition include Brachyolmia Type 2, Pseudo-Morquio syndrome type 2, and spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia of Maroteaux. Is there anything else I can help with?

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Kozlowski type is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the skeletal system. It is characterized by vetebral platyspondyly, overfaced pedicles, scoliosis, and mild metaphyseal abnormalities in the pelvis. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. It can also be referred to as Jequier-Kozlowski syndrome, SMD Kozlowski type, dysmorphism arthrogryposis skeletal maturation advanced, or skeletal dysplasia Jequier-Kozlowski type.

alkuraya kucinskas syndrome, also known as alkuvaus syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects many parts of the body. It is caused by mutations in the ALK gene, which is located on chromosome 2. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Symptoms of alkuvaus syndrome can include cleft palate, clubfoot, short stature, and intellectual disability. The severity of the symptoms varies among affected individuals and can range from mild to severe. In some cases, the disorder is so severe that it is incompatible with life.

There is no cure for alkuvaus syndrome, but early intervention and proper management can help improve quality of life. Treatment may include surgery to correct physical abnormalities such as cleft palate or clubfoot, as well as speech therapy and other specialized care. With appropriate support and care, many individuals with alkuvaus syndrome are able to lead fulfilling lives despite their challenges.

steatocystoma multiplex is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the presence of multiple benign sebaceous cysts on the skin, which have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT17 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. The condition has an exact synonym of multiple sebaceous cysts and sebocystomatosis.

CMT2A2B is a subtype of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT) characterized by onset of peripheral neuropathy in the first years of life. It is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in the MFN2 gene located on chromosome 1p36.2. The exact synonyms for CMT2A2B include AR-CMT2, Ouvrier type, CMT2, SEOAN due to MFN2 deficiency, autosomal recessive Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, Ouvrier type, and severe early-onset axonal neuropathy due to MFN2 deficiency.

User, Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2DD is indeed a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2. It is also classified as an autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be inherited from one parent and passed on to the next generation with a high probability. Additionally, it has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A1 gene on chromosome 1p13.1. It is also known as ATP1A1-related CMT2, ATP1A1-related autosomal dominant Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2, CMT2DD, Charcot-Marie-Tooth neuropathy, type 2DD.

CMT2EE, also known as Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2, is a form of CMT that primarily affects the lower limbs and has a slow progression. It usually starts in childhood or adolescence and is caused by mutations in the MPV17 gene located on chromosome 2p23.3. The exact synonym for this condition is CMT2EE, which stands for Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, axonal type 2.

CMT1G, also known as Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1g, is a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease that affects the peripheral nerves. It is caused by mutations in the PMP2 gene located on chromosome 8q21.13 and typically presents with distal muscle weakness and atrophy, starting in the first or second decade of life. The disease has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and can be diagnosed through genetic testing.

Stiff Skin Syndrome, also known as Stickler Syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. It is an autosomal dominant condition, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the disease. TheFBN1 gene on chromosome 15q21.1 is responsible for causing Stiff Skin Syndrome. This disorder results in the production of abnormal collagen, which leads to the thickening and hardening of the skin, as well as other connective tissue problems. Some people with this condition may also experience hearing loss, vision problems, and joint stiffness.

Overhydrated hereditary stomatocytosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by macrocytic hemolytic anemia and monovalent cation leak from red blood cells. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the RHAG gene on chromosome 6p12.3, and it is also known as OHS or potassium sodium disorder of erythrocyte.

text: Sturge-Weber Syndrome (SWS) is a rare vascular disorder characterized by abnormal blood vessels in the brain, skin and eyes. It is caused by a somatic mutation in the GNAQ gene on chromosome 9q21.2. The condition can cause various symptoms such as seizures, blindness, facial pain, leptomeningeal angiomatosis (abnormal blood vessels in the brain and spinal cord), skin abnormalities, and glaucoma. It is also known by several other names including Sturge-Weber-Dimitri Syndrome, Sturge-Weber-Krabbe Angiomatosis, Encephalofacial Angiomatosis, Encephalotrigeminal Angiomatosis, Fourth Phacomatosis, Leptomeningeal Angiomatosis, and Meningeal Capillary Angiomatosis.

Hypoplastic or aplastic tibia with polydactyly is a condition that is characterized by a congenital underdevelopment of the tibia, which can result in short stature and other skeletal abnormalities. It is often associated with preaxial polydactyly, meaning an extra finger or toes on the hands and feet. This condition has a genetic basis and is typically inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. It is also known by several other names, including Werner mesomelic syndrome, absence of tibia with polydactyly, hypoplastic tibiae-postaxial polydactyly syndrome, and tibial hemimelia-polysyndactyly-triphalangeal thumb syndrome.

Trichodontoosseous syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of hair, teeth, bones, and craniofacial structure. It is caused by mutations in the DLX3 gene on chromosome 17q21.33 and is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. The condition is characterized by curly kinky hair at birth, enamel hypoplasia, taurodontism (an abnormal tooth shape), thickening of the cortical bones, and variable expression of craniofacial morphology. It has been also known as TDO syndrome or tricho-dento-osseous syndrome.

familial isolated trichomegaly is an eyelid disease characterized by the prolonged anagen phase of the eyelash hairs resulting in extremely long eyelashes. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FGF5 gene on chromosome 4q21.21. The term "familial" indicates that this disease is inherited and can be passed down through generations of a family, while the term "isolated" implies that it is not part of a larger syndrome or class of diseases.
Treatment for familial isolated trichomegaly may involve removing excess eyelashes with tweezers or using electrolysis to destroy the hair follicle. Other options include using creams or lotions containing tretinoin, alpha hydroxy acid, or ketoconazole to help manage irritation and reduce inflammation. In severe cases, a surgical procedure called blepharoplasty may be necessary to remove excess skin, fat, and eyelashes from the upper and lower lids.
It's important for individuals with this condition to follow good hygiene practices to prevent infections and irritation caused by their long eyelashes. They should also avoid using harsh chemicals or hot water when washing their face, as these can cause irritation and damage the eyelashes.
Familial isolated trichomegaly is a relatively rare condition, but with proper care and management, individuals with this condition can lead normal lives.

Retinal vasculopathy with cerebral leukodystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the adult onset of microvascular endotheliopathy resulting in central nervous system degeneration, progressive loss of vision, stroke, motor impairment and cognitive decline. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in TREX1 on chromosome 3p21.31.

Congenital vertical talus, also known as CVT or congenital convex foot, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the feet and ankles. It is characterized by abnormal bone growth and joint alignment issues in these areas, often leading to pain, swelling, and limited mobility.

CVT can be caused by various factors, including genetic mutations or chromosomal abnormalities, exposure to certain medications during pregnancy, or other environmental influences. In some cases, it may also be inherited from a parent who carries the gene but does not have symptoms themselves.

Treatment for congenital vertical talus typically involves surgery and physical therapy to realign the bones and improve mobility. Early intervention is crucial in ensuring the best possible outcome, as untreated or delayed treatment can lead to long-term complications and disability.

Autosomal dominant vitreoretinochoroidopathy is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This condition affects the retina and can cause problems with vision. It is passed down through families, which means that if one parent has it, there's a good chance their child will also have it. The exact cause of this condition isn't known, but researchers believe it may be related to mutations in certain genes. Symptoms can include abnormal pigmentation in the retina and other eye development issues. In some cases, it can lead to blindness if left untreated.

snowflake vitreoretinal degeneration (SVD) is a type of autosomal dominant eye disease that affects the vitreous humor, retina, and other structures within the eye. It is characterized by early-onset cataract formation, fibrillar degeneration of the vitreous humor, minute crystalline deposits in the neurosensory retina, and a higher risk of retinal detachment compared to age-matched controls. SVD has been linked to mutations in the KCNJ13 gene on chromosome 2q37.1.

Weyers acrofacial dysostosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by dental anomalies, nail dystrophy, postaxial polydactyly, and mild short stature. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the genes EVC2 or EVC on chromosome 4p16.2. The condition is also known by other names such as Curry-Hall syndrome, WAD, Weyers acrodental dysostosis, and acrofacial dysostosis, Weyers type.

familial woolly hair syndrome is a type of hair disease that affects the growth and appearance of hair. It is characterized by fine, tightly curled hair that grows slowly and stops growing after a few inches. The hair shafts are also abnormal, displaying trichorrhexis nodosa, which is a condition where the hair breaks easily. Additionally, the ends of the hair are tapered.

Autosomal dominant woolly hair, also known as ADWH, is a type of familial woolly hair syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KRT74 gene on chromosome 12q13.13. It is characterized by an increased density and curl pattern of hair, often accompanied by other physical characteristics such as thick eyebrows, big ears, and a prominent chin.

Autosomal recessive woolly hair type 3 is a genetic disorder that is caused by mutations in the KRT24 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. It is characterized by thick, curly hair and can be inherited from affected parents. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation of the KRT24 gene.

dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis is a type of hemolytic anemia characterized by altered intracellular cation content and cellular dehydration of erythocytes resulting in increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentrations and altered cell shapes. It has the exact synonyms hereditary desiccytosis and hereditary xerocytosis.

That is correct. Dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PIEZO1 gene on chromosome 16q24.3. It has exact synonyms such as pseudohyperkalemia edinburgh, pseudohyperkalemia familial 1, and dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 1 with or without pseudohyperkalemia and/or perinatal edema.

Dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease in which a person has a mutation in the KCNN4 gene on chromosome 19q13.31, leading to a condition known as xerocytosis Gardos or dehydrated stomatocytosis. This condition is characterized by abnormal fluid balance and a decreased ability to produce saliva, resulting in dry mouth and potential dental problems. It can be inherited from one or both parents who are carriers of the mutated gene.

Gillespie Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the eye, brain, and spinal cord. It is also known as Aniridia-Cerebellar Ataxia-Intellectual Disability Syndrome (ACAIDS). The syndrome is caused by mutations in the ITPR1 gene on chromosome 3p26.1. Gillespie Syndrome can cause a range of symptoms, including iris hypoplasia, congenital hypotonia, cerebellar hypoplasia, cognitive impairment, and ataxia. In some cases, it may also be associated with other medical conditions or complications.

The ASA triad consists of three conditions: asthma, aspirin intolerance, and nasal polyps. These conditions can occur together and cause respiratory problems. Asthma is a chronic condition that affects the airways in the lungs, making it difficult to breathe. Nasal polyps are noncancerous growths in the nasal passages that can obstruct breathing. Aspirin intolerance occurs when the body has an allergic reaction to aspirin and other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). This reaction can cause a range of symptoms, including asthma attacks and nasal polyps. Together, these conditions make up the ASA triad and can lead to serious respiratory problems if not properly managed.

Behr Syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the nervous system. It is characterized by early-onset optic atrophy, ataxia, pyramidal signs, spasticity, and intellectual disability. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the OPA1 gene on chromosome 3q29. It is also known as Abortive cerebellar ataxia (BEHRS) and optic atrophy in early childhood, associated with ataxia, spasticity, mental retardation, and posterior column sensory loss.

Opitz C (c) syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant genetic disorder characterized by several developmental abnormalities. These can include craniosynostosis, which causes an early fusion of the skull bones, and other physical features such as hypertelorism (broadly spaced eyes), down-turned mouth, small ears, and a broad thumbs.
The syndrome is caused by mutations in the CD96 gene on chromosome 3q13.1-q13.2 and can lead to intellectual disability, motor skill delay, and other developmental issues.

Hereditary arterial and articular multiple calcification syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by adult-onset calcification in the lower extremities, hand and foot capsule joints. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NT5E gene on chromosome 6q14.3. The condition is also known by synonyms such as CALJA, arterial calcification and distal joint calcification, arterial calcification due to CD73 deficiency, calcification of joints and arteries.

carboxypeptidase N deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to process certain proteins. It occurs when the CPN1 gene on chromosome 10q24.2 is either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutated. This leads to low levels of carboxypeptidase N in the blood, which can cause a range of symptoms including episodic angioedema, chronic urticaria, asthma and allergic hypersensitivity. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome is a type of syndrome.
dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome is a type of medical condition with a genetic component.
dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome has definition A syndrome characterized by dilated cardiomyopathy and hypergonadotropic hypogonadism that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the LMNA gene on chromosome 1q22..
dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome has exact synonym Malouf syndrome.

dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome has exact synonym genital anomaly with cardiomyopathy.

Carnitine acylcarnitine translocase deficiency is an autosomal recessive disorder that affects the metabolism of fats. It causes various problems, including fasting-induced hypoketotic hypoglycemia, hyperammonemia, elevated creatine kinase and transaminases, dicarboxylic aciduria, very low free carnitine and abnormal acylcarnitine profile with marked elevation of the long-chain acylcarnitines. The disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A20 gene on chromosome 3p21.31. It is also known as CACT deficiency and CACTD.

Martsolf Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of several body systems, including the eyes and brain. It is caused by mutations in the RAB3GAP2 gene on chromosome 1q41 and can result in intellectual deficit, congenital cataract, and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. The syndrome has also been referred to as Cataract-Intellectual Disability-Hypogonadism Syndrome.

Gordon Holmes Syndrome, also known as CAHH and GDHS, is an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by progressive cognitive decline, dementia, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and variable movement disorders resulting from disordered ubiquitination that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RNF216 gene on chromosome 7p22.1.
It is also known as LHRH deficiency and ataxia, cerebellar ataxia-hypogonadism syndrome, and luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone deficiency with ataxia.

Greenberg dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the skeletal system. It is characterized by a defect in cholesterol biosynthesis, which results in fetal hydrops, severe shortening of all long bones with a moth-eaten radiographic appearance, platyspondyly, disorganization of chondroosseous calcification, and ectopic ossification centers. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in LBR on chromosome 1q42.12. It is also known by other names such as GRBGD, Greenberg skeletal dysplasia, HEM dysplasia, Skeletal dysplasia, Greenberg type, autosomal recessive lethal chondrodystrophy with congenital hydrops, and hydrops-ectopic calcification-moth-eaten syndrome.

Coach syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by cerebellar vermis hypo/aplasia, oligophrenia, ataxia, ocular coloboma, and hepatic fibrosis. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in one of three genes: TMEM67, CC2D2A, and RPGRIL. The exact synonyms for this condition are Gentile syndrome, JS-H, Joubert syndrome with congenital hepatic fibrosis, Joubert syndrome with hepatic defect, and cerebellar vermis hypo/aplasia, oligophrenia, congenital ataxia, ocular coloboma, and hepatic fibrosis.

Cohen Syndrome, also known as Pepper Syndrome and Hypotonia, obesity, and prominent incisors, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by several physical and developmental abnormalities. These include facial dysmorphism (an altered facial structure), microcephaly (small head size), truncal obesity (excessive fat around the belly area), impaired intellectual development, progressive retinopathy (abnormal blood vessels in the eyes), and intermittent congenital neutropenia (a lack of certain types of white blood cells).
Cohen Syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VPS13B gene, which is located on chromosome 8q22.2. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that to develop the syndrome, an individual must have two copies of the altered gene (one from each parent).
It's important to note that while Cohen Syndrome can cause a variety of health issues, it does not have a direct impact on intelligence. With proper medical care and support, individuals with Cohen Syndrome can lead full and meaningful lives.
Congenital heart defects, hamartomas of the tongue, and polysyndactyly is a type of autosomal recessive disorder.

Plasminogen deficiency type I, also known as hypoplasminogenemia, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the production of plasminogen, a protein critical for blood clotting and tissue repair. It results from mutations in the PLG gene on chromosome 6q26. This condition causes chronic mucosal pseudomembranous lesions, which typically present as ligneous conjunctivitis (a thickening of the conjunctiva), but can also affect other organs such as the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts. Individuals with this disorder are at an increased risk for infections and may require frequent monitoring and treatment to manage their symptoms.

Distal arthrogryposis type 10 is a condition characterized by limited or absent movement in the distal joints of the body, such as fingers and toes. It is typically inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that only one copy of the gene is needed for the condition to be expressed. The condition has been linked to a mutation on chromosome 2q31.3-q32.1 and can also be known by other names such as DA10, plantar flexion contracture, short Achilles tendon, and short tendo calcaneus.
Distal arthrogryposis type 5D, also known as DA5D, is a type of distal

Congenital contractural arachnodactyly is a type of distal arthrogryposis, which refers to a non-progressive congenital musculoskeletal disorder that affects the joint mobility and causes multiple contractures (immobility of several limb segments). It has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance, meaning that it is passed down through families. The disorder is characterized by the presence of arachnodactyly, which are fingers with an unusual configuration, scoliosis, and crumpled ears. Additionally, there may be other physical abnormalities such as clubfoot, talipes equinovarus, and hip dysplasia.
Congenital contractural arachnodactyly is often diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can lead to severe disability if not treated properly. Treatment options may include surgery, physical therapy, and assistive devices such as braces or wheelchairs. With proper care and management, individuals with congenital contractural arachnodactyly can have a good quality of life.

distal arthrogryposis type 1 is a condition that affects the joints in the hands and feet. It is characterized by contractures, or permanent flexion of the fingers and toes, which can make it difficult for individuals to move their limbs freely. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the condition, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. Distal arthrogryposis type 1 does not typically affect the face or other parts of the body, although some individuals may experience additional physical and developmental challenges related to this condition.

distal arthrogryposis type 1a (DA1A) is a genetic disorder that affects the joints in the extremities, specifically the hands and feet. It is caused by mutations in the TPM2 gene on chromosome 9p13.3. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the altered gene is enough to cause the disorder.
DA1A can lead to severe joint stiffness and contractures in the affected limbs, resulting in limited mobility and deformities. It is important to seek medical attention for those affected by this condition to manage their symptoms effectively.

Distal arthrogryposis type 1b, also known as DA1B, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and joints in the arms and legs. It is caused by a mutation in the MYBPC1 gene on chromosome 12q23.2, which leads to abnormalities in the growth of collagen, a protein that provides strength and flexibility to connective tissues such as tendons and ligaments.
DA1B can cause various symptoms, including stiffness, joint contractures, limited mobility, and deformities of the arms and legs. The severity of these symptoms varies among affected individuals and depends on the specific genetic changes that occur. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to manage the condition effectively and prevent complications.
Genetic counseling can help families understand their risk and make informed decisions about family planning. There is no cure for DA1B, but physical therapy, assistive devices, and medications may be used to improve mobility and quality of life.

distal arthrogryposis type 2b is a condition characterized by contractures of the distal joints of the limbs, triangular face, downslanting palpebral fissures, small mouth, and high arched palate. It is also known as DA2B, Freeman-Sheldon syndrome variant, and Sheldon-Hall syndrome.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b1, also known as DA2B1, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and joints of the limbs. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The condition is characterized by limited movement of the fingers, toes, wrists, and ankles, as well as an increased risk of developing other health problems such as contractures and foot deformities. Treatment typically involves physical therapy, splints, and medications to manage pain and improve mobility.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b2 is a condition that affects the joints in the extremities, particularly those in the distal part of the body. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that it can be inherited from one parent and can be passed down through generations. The TNNT3 gene on chromosome 11p15.5 is mutated in individuals with this condition, leading to the formation of abnormal protein structures in muscle tissue.
This disorder can cause a range of symptoms, including joint stiffness, limited mobility, and contractures (fixed deformities). It is important for individuals with distal arthrogryposis type 2b2 to receive proper medical care and support to manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the joints in the extremities. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. The exact synonym for this condition is distal arthrogryposis type 2B3 (Sheldon-Hall).

Distal arthrogryposis type 7, also known as Dutch-Kentucky syndrome or Hecht syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by a distal limb contracture and other congenital anomalies. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the MYH8 gene on chromosome 17p13.1, which encodes for the muscle-specific actin protein. This leads to reduced contractility of the muscles responsible for flexion of the fingers and wrists, resulting in difficulty in opening the mouth fully and pseudocamptodactyly. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is sufficient to cause the disorder. It is also known as trismus-pseudocamptodactyly syndrome due to the presence of these two main features.

Freeman-Sheldon Syndrome, also known as Craniocarpotarsal Dysplasia or Whistling Face Syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by several distinctive features. These include microstomia (a small mouth), a whistling appearance of the mouth due to the absence of teeth, a distinctive facies (facial appearance), clubfoot, and joint contractures. The syndrome affects both the skull and the feet, leading to severe developmental issues and a range of physical challenges throughout the individual's life.

distal arthrogryposis type 2a is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscle and bone development. It is also known as Freeman-Sheldon syndrome when there is a heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. The definition of distal arthrogryposis type 2a includes this synonym DA2A and distal arthrogryposis type 2A (Freeman-Sheldon).

Autosomal recessive whistling face syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the face and upper jaw. It is characterized by underdevelopment of the midface, which can lead to a thin or wrinkled appearance in the cheeks and around the mouth. In addition, there may be an abnormal whistling sound when breathing, due to weakness in the muscles responsible for speech and breathing. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Distal arthrogryposis type 3, also known as DA3 or Gordon syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by distal arthrogryposis (a condition in which the joints in the arms and legs do not develop properly), short stature, cleft palate, and camptodactyly (bent thumbs). It is caused by mutations in the PIEZO2 gene on chromosome 18p11.22-p11.21 and is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person has an increased risk of developing the disorder if one of their parents passes it on to them.

distal arthrogryposis type 5 is a condition that affects the joints in the extremities. It is characterized by limited range of motion and stiffness in the joints, particularly in the hands and feet. It often leads to deformities in these areas and can cause pain and difficulty moving. Distal arthrogryposis type 5 is also associated with ocular abnormalities, such as cataracts and glaucoma. The condition is usually inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that it can be passed down through families. It is caused by a mutation in the PIEZO2 gene on chromosome 18p11.22-p11.21. This type of distal arthrogryposis is also known as DA5, and it can cause oculomotor limitation and electroretinal anomalies.

Distal arthrogryposis type 6, also known as DA6, is a condition characterized by distal arthrogryposis (a congenital joint contracture affecting the fingers and wrist) and sensorineural deafness. It is part of a group of disorders called arthrogryposis, which are characterized by limited or fixed joint movement due to muscle and connective tissue abnormalities.
Sensorineural deafness, also known as inner ear disease, refers to problems affecting the inner ear that lead to hearing loss. In DA6, this condition is thought to be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.
It's important to note that while some cases of arthrogryposis may present with additional features such as craniofacial abnormalities, heart defects, or other anomalies, this information is not available for DA6 specifically. However, it does highlight the importance of seeking genetic counseling if a family member has been affected by arthrogryposis to understand their risk better and make informed decisions about future pregnancies.

Distal arthrogryposis type 4, also known as DA4 or arthrogryposis-severe scoliosis syndrome, is a condition characterized by severe distal joint stiffness and scoliosis. It is classified under the broader category of distal arthrogryposis, which refers to a group of congenital disorders that affect the normal development of the limbs and joints.
Distal arthrogryposis type 4 may also be referred to by other names such as DAIID or arthrogryposis-severe scoliosis syndrome, but it is important to use the term "distal arthrogryposis type 4" consistently throughout a given discussion or medical record.
If you have any questions about distal arthrogryposis type 4 or would like more information, please feel free to ask.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 4, also known as SCA24, SCASI, or cerebellar ataxia-saccadic intrusion syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by ataxic gait with spasticity and hyperreflexia of the lower limbs. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VPS13D gene on chromosome 1p36.22-p36.21.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 3, also known as SCABD or SCAR3, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by spinocerebellar ataxia with optic and cochlear degeneration. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 6p23-p21. The condition is also known as autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia type 3, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia-blindness-deafness syndrome, and autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia-blindness-hearing loss syndrome.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 23, also known as SCAR23, is a genetic disorder characterized by epilepsy, intellectual disability, and gait ataxia. It is caused by mutations in the TDP2 gene on chromosome 6p22.3. The condition has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the disorder.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia type 22 (SCAR22) is a genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum, which is part of the brain responsible for balance and coordination. It is caused by mutations in the VWA3B gene located on chromosome 2q11.2. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease. Symptoms of SCAR22 typically start in childhood and may include poor balance and coordination, difficulty walking, and muscle weakness. The condition can progress over time and affect other parts of the body as well.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 24 (SCAR24) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that results from mutations in the UBA5 gene on chromosome 3q22.1. It has been defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UBA5 gene. The term SCAR24 is also used as an exact synonym for this condition.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 27, also known as SCAR27, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by adult onset of progressive gait difficulties and other cerebellar signs. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GDAP2 gene located on chromosome 1p12.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 6, also known as SCAR6, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by the onset of nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia in infancy, without intellectual disability. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in a region on chromosome 20q11-q13. It is also known as infantile-onset autosomal recessive nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia.

combined d 2 and l 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means it is passed down through the family genes but does not show up in every generation. It is characterized by neonatal-onset encephalopathy with severe hypotonia, intractable seizures, respiratory distress, and lack of psychomotor development resulting in early death. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A1 gene on chromosome 22q11.21.

Corneal dystrophy with progressive deafness, also known as CDPD or Harboyan syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by congenital corneal endothelial dystrophy and progressive, postlingual sensorineural hearing loss. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC4A11 gene on chromosome 20p13. It is important to note that CDPD is not related to the more common form of corneal dystrophy, which is usually inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.

Temtamy Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body. It is characterized by craniofacial dysmorphism, ocular coloboma, seizures, and brain abnormalities including partial or complete absence of the corpus callosum. The syndrome has a material basis in mutations in the C12ORF57 gene on chromosome 12p13.31. It has been referred to with other names such as Temtamy-Shalash Syndrome, craniofacial dysmorphism with ocular coloboma absent corpus callosum and aortic dilatation, craniofacial dysmorphism-coloboma-corpus callosum agenesis syndrome, and dysmorphism, corpus callosum agenesis and colobomas.

text: Yes, ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia is a type of primary hyperaldosteronism. It is characterized by multiple bilateral adrenocortical nodules that cause a striking enlargement of the adrenal gland and production of an excess of cortisol. Some common synonyms for this condition include AIMAH, MMAD, Cushing syndrome due to macronodular adrenal hyperplasia, and primary macronodular adrenal hyperplasia. It is important to note that these terms are used interchangeably in medical literature, although some sources may use different terminology.

ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia 1 (AIMAH1) is a type of ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia. It has an ACTH-independent nature, as it is caused by somatic mutations in the GNAS gene on chromosome 20q13.32. This condition has also been referred to as AIMAH1.

acth independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia 2, also known as AIMAH2, is a type of ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia. This condition occurs due to a combination of autosomal dominant and second hit somatic mutations in the ARMC5 gene on chromosome 16p11.2.

Ventriculomegaly cystic kidney disease is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the onset in utero of dilated cerebral ventricles and microscopic renal tubular cysts. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heteroygous mutations in the CRB2 gene located on chromosome 9q33.3. The exact synonyms for this condition include congenital nephrosis-cerebral ventriculomegaly syndrome, cystic kidney disease with ventriculomegaly, and ventriculomegaly with cystic kidney disease.
D-glyceric aciduria is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Doors Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems of the body, including the ears, bones, and brain. It is caused by mutations in the TBC1D24 gene on chromosome 16p13.3, which is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.
The symptoms of Doors Syndrome typically begin in infancy or early childhood and may include sensorineural deafness (hearing loss), onychodystrophy (a disorder affecting the nails), osteodystrophy (bone abnormalities), seizures, and intellectual disability.
Without treatment, the symptoms of Doors Syndrome can worsen over time and lead to serious complications. However, early diagnosis and intervention can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected by this rare genetic disorder.

High myopia sensorineural deafness syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by severe myopia and moderate to profound, bilateral, progressive sensorineural hearing loss. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLITRK6 gene on chromosome 13q31.1. It is also known as DFNMYP and deafness and myopia syndrome.

dihydropyrimidinase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of pyrimidine, an important component of DNA. It occurs due to a lack or malfunctioning of the enzyme dihydropyrimidinase, which is responsible for breaking down uracil and thymine in the body. This leads to the accumulation of uracil and thymine in the body, causing symptoms such as high levels of 5-carboxy-urea (5,6-dihydrouracil) and 5,6-dihydrothymine (5,6-dihydrothymine) in urine.
Dihydropyrimidinase deficiency can be inherited as an autosomal recessive trait, meaning that a person needs to inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It is also possible for dihydropyrimidinase deficiency to be inherited in a compound heterozygous manner, where both parents pass on one working and one non-working copy of the gene.
Symptoms of dihydropyrimidinase deficiency can vary widely depending on the severity of the enzyme deficiency, but may include gastrointestinal symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, nausea and vomiting, as well as skin rashes, hair loss, and joint pain. In severe cases, dihydropyrimidinase deficiency can lead to life-threatening complications such as seizures, coma, and even death if not treated promptly with appropriate medical interventions.
Diagnosis of dihydropyrimidinase deficiency typically involves a combination of laboratory tests, including urine analysis for high levels of 5,6-dihydrouracil and 5,6-dihydrothymine, as well as genetic testing to confirm the presence of mutations in the DPYS gene.
Treatment options for dihydropyrimidinase deficiency depend on the severity of the condition and can include dietary changes, medication, and other supportive measures to manage symptoms. In some cases, enzyme replacement therapy may be recommended for individuals with severe or life-threatening forms of the disorder.

Familial erythrocytosis 8, also known as BPGM deficiency or diphosphoglycerate mutase deficiency of erythrocyte, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by an excessive production of red blood cells (erythrocytosis) and in some cases hemolytic anemia. This condition is caused by a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BPGM gene on chromosome 7q33. The exact synonyms for this disorder include ECYT8, DPGM deficiency, and hemolytic anemia due to diphosphoglycerate mutase deficiency.

Familial erythrocytosis 7, also known as alpha-globin type erythrocytosis or primary polycythemia, is a condition characterized by high oxygen affinity hemoglobin and compensatory polycythemia due to heterozygous mutations in either the HBA2 or HBA1 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. This type of erythrocytosis has an exact synonym of ECYT7, and it can be considered a form of primary polycythemia with this specific genetic basis.

familial erythrocytosis 6 is a type of primary polycythemia that is characterized by high oxygen affinity hemoglobin and compensatory polycythemia. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the HBB gene on chromosome 11p15.4. Familial erythrocytosis 6, also known as ECYT6 or beta-globin type erythrocytosis, is a condition that causes an increase in red blood cells and can lead to anemia if left untreated. It is important for those with this condition to have regular checkups and follow their healthcare provider's recommendations for treatment.

Congenital sucrase isomaltase deficiency (CSID) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the ability to digest certain carbohydrates, specifically oligosaccharides and disaccharides. It occurs due to a genetic mutation on chromosome 3q26.1 that results in the deficiency of sucrase-isomaltase enzymes. This condition can lead to malabsorption of these carbohydrates, which can cause a range of symptoms depending on the severity and the amount of undigested carbohydrates present in the diet.
CSID can be diagnosed through a combination of medical history, physical examination, laboratory tests, and imaging studies. Treatment typically involves a strict low-disaccharide diet to minimize the intake of oligosaccharides and disaccharides that are not properly digested by the body. In some cases, enzyme replacement therapy may also be recommended to supplement the missing sucrase-isomaltase enzymes.
It is important for individuals with CSID to work closely with a healthcare professional who has experience in managing this condition to develop an appropriate treatment plan that meets their specific needs and monitors their response to treatment over time.

autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 99 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual, severe to profound sensorineural hearing loss without vestibular dysfunction that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM132E gene on chromosome 17q12.
autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 99 is also known as DFNB99 and autosomal recessive deafness 99.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 57 (DFNB57) is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by symmetric bilateral moderate to severe hearing loss that has a genetic basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PDZD7 gene on chromosome 10q24.31.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 113 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness that is characterized by postlingual progressive hearing impairment and has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CEACAM16 gene on chromosome 19q13. It also has synonyms such as DFNB113 and autosomal recessive deafness 113.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 112 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness that is characterized by postlingual progressive sensorineural hearing impairment and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the BDP1 gene on chromosome 5q13.2. It has synonyms such as DFNB112 and autosomal recessive deafness 112.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 100 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness that is characterized by prelingual onset of profound sensorineural deafness without vestibular involvement that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PPIP5K2 gene on chromosome 5q21.1.. It is also known as DFNB100 and autosomal recessive deafness 100.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 109, also known as DFNB109 or autosomal recessive deafness 109, is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by bilateral congenital severe to profound sensorineural hearing loss and vestibular dysplasia without balance or movement issues that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ESRP1 gene on chromosome 8q22.1.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 111, also known as DFNB111 or autosomal recessive deafness 111, is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by early-onset, moderate to severe sensorineural hearing loss with no vestibular involvement that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MPZL2 gene on chromosome 11q23.33.<|end

autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 94 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual profound sensorineural hearing loss that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NARS2 gene on chromosome 11q14.1.<|endoftext|>

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 114 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness that is characterized by congenital profound sensorineural hearing loss with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GRAP gene on chromosome 17p11.2. It has the exact synonym DFNB114 and autosomal recessive deafness 114.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 115 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by onset in early childhood of severe sensorineural hearing impairment that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SPNS2 gene on chromosome 17p13.2. It is also known as DFNB115 and autosomal recessive deafness 115.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 110, also known as DFNB110, is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual, bilateral hearing loss with mutations in the COCH gene on chromosome 14q12.

Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome is a type of infancy electroclinical syndrome.
Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.
Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome is a type of something that at least existence starts during some infantile onset.
