Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome has exact synonym EPRPDC.
Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome has exact synonym RE-PED-WC.

Rolandic epilepsy, paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia, and writer's cramp syndrome has exact synonym Rolandic-type focal motor epilepsy and exercise-induced dystonia.

Congenital lactase deficiency is a condition where an individual is unable to produce enough lactase, the enzyme that breaks down lactose, due to genetic factors. This leads to difficulty digesting breast milk or formula containing lactose and can cause symptoms such as diarrhea, abdominal pain, bloating, and gas. It is a type of autosomal recessive inheritance and has a material basis in the homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LCT gene on chromosome 2q21.3.

SSPS, or Schopf-Schulz-Passarge Syndrome, is a rare autosomal dominant disorder characterized by several distinctive features. These include multiple eyelid apocrine hidrocystomas, palmoplantar keratoderma, hypotrichosis (hairlessness), hypodontia (missing teeth), and nail dystrophy. The condition has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the WNT10A gene on chromosome 2q35 being the primary cause.

Synonyms for SSPS include eccrine tumors-ectodermal dysplasia, keratosis palmoplantaris-cystic eyelids-hypodontia-hypotrichosis syndrome, and palmoplantar hyperkeratosis-cystic eyelids-hypodontia-hypotrichosis syndrome. It is important to note that SSPS can be misdiagnosed as other conditions due to the overlapping symptoms with other ectodermal dysplasias.

In summary, SSPS is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a combination of distinctive features, primarily affecting the skin and hair/nails. The primary cause of the condition is mutations in the WNT10A gene on chromosome 2q35.

ectopia lentis with ectopia of pupil is a type of eye disease that occurs due to the displacement of the lenses and the pupils in association with other ocular anomalies, which has a genetic basis. It is caused by mutations in the ADAMTSL4 gene on chromosome 1q21.2. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease.

ECTD syndrome, also known as ectodermal dysplasia with ectrodactyly and macular dystrophy (EEM), is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of skin, hair, nails, teeth, and sweat glands. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that to develop the disease, an individual must inherit two copies of the abnormal gene, one from each parent.

People with ECTD syndrome often have a missing or underdeveloped thumbs and big toes (ectrodactyly), as well as other physical abnormalities such as skin that is thick and scaly, sparse hair, and missing teeth. They may also experience vision problems due to macular dystrophy, which affects the central part of the eye.

There is no cure for ECTD syndrome, but early intervention and management can help improve the quality of life for those affected by the disorder. Treatment options may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, and orthodontic care to address any functional limitations caused by the condition. Surgical procedures may also be considered to correct certain physical abnormalities.

ECTD13 is a rare genetic disorder characterized by severe oligodontia, abnormal hair and skin, and other ectodermal defects. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KREMEN1 gene on chromosome 22q12.1.

Ectodermal dysplasia 15 (also known as ectodermal dysplasia 15, hypohidrotic/hair type) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the onset in early childhood of hypotrichosis and the absence of sweating except with extreme exercise, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CST6 gene on chromosome 11q13.1.

Ectodermal dysplasia 12, also known as hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This means that if one parent has the gene for this condition, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the gene and develop the disease.
Ectodermal dysplasia 12 is characterized by abnormal development of the ectoderm, which can lead to a variety of problems including hypoplasia or aplasia of sweat glands, hair, nails, and teeth. This condition can also cause anhidrosis, a lack of sweating, and other symptoms such as dry skin, bone deformities, and missing teeth.
Treatment for ectodermal dysplasia 12 typically focuses on managing the symptoms and improving quality of life. This may include regular bathing to help keep the skin moisturized, wearing protective clothing or sunblock to prevent sunburn, and using fluoride toothpaste to promote healthy teeth and gums. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct bone deformities or other issues related to this condition.
It is important for individuals with ectodermal dysplasia 12 to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a comprehensive treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and symptoms.<|end_of_text|>

ectodermal dysplasia 11a is a medical condition that affects the development of the skin, hair, nails and teeth. It is caused by a mutation in the EDARADD gene on chromosome 1q42-q43. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting the condition if one of their parents passes it on. Symptoms may include dry and sparse hair, nails that are thin and brittle, and a lack of sweat glands in the skin. Treatment options depend on the severity of the condition but can include medications to manage symptoms, such as antibiotics for skin infections or hormone replacement therapy for those experiencing hormonal imbalances.

ectodermal dysplasia 11b is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the development of skin, hair, nails, sweat glands and teeth. It is also known as hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia 11b or ECTD11B. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EDARADD gene on chromosome 1q42-q43. It is also known as ectodermal dysplasia 11b, hypohidrotic/hair/tooth type, autosomal recessive.

Ectodermal dysplasias are a group of disorders that affect the outermost layer of skin, hair, nails, and teeth. They can be caused by genetic factors or environmental factors. Pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia is a specific type of ectodermal dysplasia that primarily affects the hair and nails. It is characterized by onychodystrophy, which is a condition where the nails become abnormal in shape or size, and severe hypotrichosis, which is a lack of hair growth. This type of ectodermal dysplasia does not affect other areas of the body, such as the teeth or skin.

ectodermal dysplasia 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It affects the hair and nails, making them abnormally shaped or missing. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the HOXC13 gene on chromosome 12q13.13. The term "ectodermal dysplasia 9" is also known as "ECTD9" and "ectodermal dysplasia 9, hair/nail type."

Ectodermal dysplasia 5, also known as ECTD5, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that primarily affects the hair and nails. It is characterized by abnormal development of these tissues, which can result in a range of symptoms such as sparse or missing hair, thinning hair, brittle nails, and other skin abnormalities.
ECTD5 is caused by mutations in a specific region on chromosome 10q24.32-q25.1. It is also classified as a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia, which means that the primary affected tissues are the hair and nails.
It is important to note that ECTD5 has a genetic basis and is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that both copies of the gene must be mutated for the condition to be expressed.

ectodermal dysplasia 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the hair and nails. It has a material basis in mutations in the KRT85 gene on chromosome 12q13.13. This condition can be inherited in a homozygous or compound heterozygous manner. The exact synonym for this condition is ectodermal dysplasia 4, hair/nail type.
Ectodermal dysplasia 6, also known as ECTD6, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder. It specifically affects the hair and nails and has a genetic basis due to mutations on chromosome 17p12-q21.2.

ectodermal dysplasia 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the hair and nails. It is caused by mutations in the KRT74 gene on chromosome 12q13.13. The condition is also known as ectodermal dysplasia 7, hair/nail type.

Ectodermal dysplasia 8, also known as ECTD8, Fried's tooth and nail syndrome and ectodermal dysplasia 8 hair/tooth/nail type, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by hypotrichosis (hair growth), hypodontia (missing teeth) and dystrophic toenails. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in a region on chromosome 18q22.1-q22.3.

Ectodermal dysplasia 14 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the development of skin, hair, nails and teeth. It is characterized by hypotrichosis (hair growth) and hypohidrosis (abnormal sweating), as well as other abnormalities in the development of the ectodermal structures such as cystic fibrosis. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TSPEAR gene on chromosome 21q22.3.

ectodermal dysplasia 10a is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the skin, hair, and nails. It is also known as ectodermal dysplasia 10A or hypohidrotic/hair/nail type, autosomal dominant.

ectodermal dysplasia 1 is a type of hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, which is a disorder characterized by abnormal development of the skin, hair, and teeth. It is caused by mutations in the EDA gene on the X chromosome, and it is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern. The condition can cause problems with sweating, and it may also affect the development of the teeth and bones. It has been referred to as Christ-Siemens-Touraine syndrome, hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia 1, X-linked anhidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, and other similar names.

Ectodermal dysplasia 10b, also known as hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia 10b, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder. It is characterized by the underdevelopment or abnormal development of the skin, hair, nails and sweat glands. This condition can be inherited from one's parents if they both pass on the faulty gene. The exact cause of this condition is not yet known but it has been linked to mutations in the EDAR gene located on chromosome 2q13. Symptoms may include dry, scaly skin, sparse hair or no hair at all, and abnormal nail growth. It's also known as ectodermal dysplasia 10b, hypohidrotic/hair/nail type, autosomal recessive.

Proliferative vasculopathy and hydranencephaly/hydrocephaly is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the brain and spinal cord. It is caused by mutations in the FLVCR2 gene on chromosome 14q24.3, which encodes a protein involved in immune system regulation. The disorder leads to abnormal blood vessel growth in the brain and spinal cord, as well as destruction of brain tissue, resulting in a variety of physical and cognitive symptoms. There is no cure for this condition, but early intervention and management can help improve quality of life for those affected.

enterokinase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by early-onset failure to thrive, edema, hypoproteinemia, diarrhea and fat malabsorption. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMPRSS15 gene on chromosome 21q21.1.

Kohlschutter-Tonz Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple body systems, including the brain and teeth. It is characterized by severe developmental delays, early onset seizures, spasticity, and abnormal tooth development. The syndrome has a material basis in mutations of the ROGDI gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. It is also known by several other names, such as KTZS, Kohlschutter's Syndrome, amelocerebrohypohidrotic syndrome, epilepsy and yellow teeth, epilepsy dementia amelogenesis imperfecta, and epilepsy-dementia-amelogenesis imperfecta syndrome.

Hyaline fibromatosis syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects connective tissue. It is characterized by the abnormal growth of hyalinized fibrous tissue, especially around the subcutaneous regions on the scalp, ears, neck, face, hands, and feet. Additionally, it can also cause gingival hypertrophy, joint contractures, and osteolytic bone lesions. This disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ANTXR2 gene on chromosome 4q21.21. It is also known by several other names, including HFS, inherited systemic hyalinosis, puretic syndrome, and systemic hyalinosis.

Primary hyperoxaluria type 1 is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the accumulation of calcium oxalate in various tissues due to the failure to transaminate glyoxylate, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AGXT gene on chromosome 2q37.3. It is also known as HP1, alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase deficiency, glycolic aciduria, hepatic AGT deficiency, oxalosis I, and peroxisomal alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase deficiency.

primary hyperoxaluria type 2 is a condition characterized by an excessive excretion of oxalate in the urine, recurrent kidney stones and nephrocalcinosis, and end-stage renal disease. It is caused by mutations in the GRHPR gene located on chromosome 9p13.2. The condition has synonyms such as D-glycerate dehydrogenase deficiency, HP2, L-glyceric aciduria, glyoxylate reductase/hydroxypyruvate reductase deficiency, and oxalosis II.
Primary hyperoxaluria type 3 is a condition characterized by recurring calcium oxalate stones. It is caused by mutations in the HOGA1 gene on chromosome 10q24.2.

Saul Wilson Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects bone development and causes a range of physical and mental health problems. It is characterized by early developmental delay, primarily involving speech; distinct facial features; short stature; brachydactyly (abnormally long fingers and toes); clubfoot deformities; cataracts; and microcephaly (small head size). The disorder has a material basis in heterozygous mutation of the COG4 gene on chromosome 16q22.1. It is also known as Saul-Wilson Osteodysplasia, and it can be diagnosed using genetic testing.

Yes, Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Short Stature and Behavioral Abnormalities (IDDSSAB) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the development of children. It is characterized by intellectual disability, global developmental delay, short stature, aphasia, and hypotonia. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IQSEC1 gene on chromosome 3p25.2-p25.1. It is also known by its exact synonym IDDSSBA.

Neurooculocardiogenitourinary syndrome, also known as NOCGUS, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of impaired growth and anomalies in several body systems, including the ocular, craniofacial, neurologic, cardiovascular, genitourinary, skeletal, and gastrointestinal systems. The syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the WDR37 gene on chromosome 10p15.3.

High Molecular Weight Kininogen Deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive blood coagulation disease. It is characterized by a deficiency in high molecular weight kininogen, which results in abnormal surface-mediated activation of fibrinolysis. The KNG1 gene on chromosome 3q27.3 encodes both high and low molecular weight kininogen. This condition has exact synonyms including Fitzgerald trait, HMWK deficiency, and congenital high-molecular-weight kininogen deficiency.

Familial benign fleck retina is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by a striking pattern of diffuse, yellow-white, fleck-like lesions extending to the far periphery of the retina but with no apparent visual or electrophysiologic deficits. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLA2G5 gene on chromosome 1p36.13.

Hereditary folate malabsorption is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder characterized by impaired intestinal folate absorption and impaired transport of folate into the central nervous system resulting in megaloblastic anemia, diarrhea, immune deficiency, infections, and neurologic deficits. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC46A1 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. The disorder can also be referred to as congenital defect of folate absorption or congenital folate malabsorption.

glutamate formiminotransferase deficiency is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder. It is caused by a lack of the enzyme glutamate formiminotransferase, which is involved in the metabolism of glutamate. This can lead to elevated levels of formiminoglutamate in the urine and plasma, as well as variable intellectual, developmental, and hematological phenotypes. Glutamate formiminotransferase deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the condition. The FTCD gene is located on chromosome 21q22.3 and mutations in this gene can cause the deficiency. Glutamate formiminotransferase deficiency has several synonyms, including Arakawa syndrome 1, FIGLUria, FTCD deficiency, formiminoglutamic acidemia, and formiminoglutamic aciduria. It can also be referred to as formiminotransferase cyclodeaminase deficiency or glutamate formiminotransferase deficiency syndrome.<|end_of_text|>

Essential fructosuria is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by an inability to convert fructose, a sugar found in fruit and some sweeteners, into glucose due to the absence or dysfunction of the enzyme fructokinase. This leads to elevated levels of fructose and its metabolites in the blood and urine after consuming fructose-containing foods or beverages.
It is caused by mutations in the KHK gene on chromosome 2p23.3, which encodes for the enzyme fructokinase. Essential fructosuria can lead to a variety of symptoms depending on the severity and how early it is diagnosed, including weight loss, weakness, fatigue, liver disease, and potentially life-threatening complications in severe cases.
It has been described as having a "material basis" due to its inheritance pattern being autosomal recessive, which means that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Glutamate cysteine ligase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the metabolism of amino acids. It is characterized by decreased levels of glutathione and gamma-glutamylcysteine, which are important for detoxifying the body's cells and protecting them from damage. Additionally, individuals with this condition may experience hemolytic anemia due to the buildup of gamma-glutamylcysteine in red blood cells. Glutamate cysteine ligase deficiency is caused by mutations in the GCLC gene on chromosome 6p12.1.

User, I understand that you have asked me to rewrite the statement "diffuse cystic renal dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease" in simpler terms. Here's my revised version:

Diffuse cystic renal dysplasia is a kind of inheritance where a mutation in one of your genes (BICC1 on chromosome 10q21.1) can cause it, and this mutation may also be present in unaffected parents who don't necessarily develop the disease. The exact synonyms for this condition include CYSRD, renal dysplasia diffuse cystic, and susceptibility to cystic renal dysplasia.

Neurofibromatosis type 1, also known as NF1, is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system and causes tumors to grow on nerve cells. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. NF1 typically occurs in people of all ages, but it is more common in children and young adults.

NF1 can cause a range of symptoms, including:

* Skin tumors called neurofibromas
* Freckling or brown spots on the skin (Lisch nodules)
* Bumps under the skin (papillomas)
* Weakness in muscles and bones (hypoplasia)
* Short stature
* Learning disabilities
* Ptosis (drooping eyelids)
* Scoliosis or other spinal deformities

NF1 is typically diagnosed based on a physical exam, medical history, and genetic testing. Treatment depends on the severity of symptoms and may include:

* Surgery to remove tumors (neurofibromas)
* Physical therapy to improve muscle strength and coordination
* Speech and language therapy for children with speech or language delays
* Medications to treat pain, seizures, or other symptoms

With proper treatment, most people with NF1 can lead a normal life. However, it is essential to monitor the condition closely and work with healthcare providers to manage symptoms effectively.

Hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome (HMPS) is a type of intestinal disease that is characterized by the presence of a mixture of hyperplastic, atypical juvenile, and adenomatous polyps in the colon and rectum. These polyps are benign growths that can increase the risk of developing colorectal cancer if left untreated. HMPS is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting the condition if one of their parents passes it on. Symptoms typically do not occur until later in life and can include blood in the stool, abdominal pain, and weight loss. Diagnosis is made through colonoscopy and biopsy. Treatment options may include removal of polyps or surgery to remove a portion of the affected intestine.

Hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome 1 is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome that is characterized by the presence of multiple polyps in the colon and rectum. It is caused by a heterozygous duplication of a region on chromosome 15q15.3-q22.1. The condition has been assigned to the category of hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome, which is characterized by the presence of multiple polyps in the colon and rectum.

Hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be inherited from one or both parents and can affect multiple members of the same family. It is also known as HMPS2, which has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the BMPR1A gene located on chromosome 10q23.2.

Potocki-Shaffer syndrome (PSS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects various parts of the body, including the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by craniofacial abnormalities, developmental delay, intellectual disability, multiple exostoses (bony growths on the surface of bones), and biparietal foramina (small openings in the skull). PSS is caused by a deletion of genes on chromosome 11p11.2, which leads to an imbalance in the expression of important genes involved in brain development and function.

Potocki-Shaffer syndrome can have a significant impact on an individual's life, affecting their growth and development, cognitive abilities, and overall quality of life. Treatment for PSS typically focuses on managing the symptoms and providing support to help individuals reach their full potential. This may include therapies such as speech and language therapy, occupational therapy, and physical therapy, as well as medications to address any related behavioral or psychological issues. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct craniofacial abnormalities or other physical problems associated with the disorder.

Ayame Gripp Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems of the body, including vision, hearing, and cognition. It is caused by mutations in the MAF gene located on chromosome 16q23.2. The syndrome is characterized by congenital cataracts, sensorineural hearing loss, intellectual disability, seizures, brachycephaly, a distinctive flat facial appearance, and reduced growth. It has been named after the Japanese author Ayame Gripp who wrote about the challenges faced by individuals with Down Syndrome in her book "Rainbow Stories".

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy (FAME) is a type of adolescence-adult electroclinical syndrome that is characterized by adult-onset cortical myoclonus, which typically presents as tremulous finger movements and myoclonus of the extremities. It has exact synonyms such as BAFME, FAME, FCMTE, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy, benign adult familial myoclonus epilepsy, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the SAMD12 gene on chromosome 8q24.11-q24.12. It is characterized by having a familial adult myoclonic epilepsy that starts during adulthood and has the exact synonyms BAFME1, FAME1, FCMTE1, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 1, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 1.

FAME5 is a type of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by onset of seizures in adolescence, followed by the development of cortical myoclonic tremor that has_material\_basis\_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CNTN2 gene on chromosome 1q32.1.. It is also known as FCMTE5 and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 5.
familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 4 is a type of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy, which refers to a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent seizures and muscle stiffness. It is an autosomal dominant disease, meaning that it can be inherited from one parent and affect both males and females. The YEATS2 gene on chromosome 3q27.1 is mutated in individuals with this condition, leading to the development of symptoms. It is also known as FAME4, FCMTE4, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 4.

FAME7, also known as familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 7, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It has a material basis in a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the RAPGEF2 gene on chromosome 4q32.1..

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 3 (FAME 3) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it has the potential to be passed down through generations. It typically affects individuals during their adulthood, with onset between 10 and 40 years old. This type of epilepsy is characterized by cortical tremor, mainly affecting the hands and voice, and can have a material basis in a gene called MARCHF6, which is located on chromosome 5p15.2.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 6 (FAME 6) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the TNRC6A gene on chromosome 16p12.1. It is characterized by adult onset myoclonic seizures and is considered benign with no long term consequences. The exact synonyms for FAME 6 include BAFME, FAME, FCMTE, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 6, and familial cortical myoclonal tremor and epilepsy 6.

Cleft palate, cardiac defects, and intellectual disability (CPCMR) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a combination of congenital heart defects, variable cleft lip/palate, short stature, microcephaly, and digital anomalies that have a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the MEIS2 gene on chromosome 15q14. It has been defined as a syndrome with these characteristics.

Proprotein convertase 1 3 deficiency, also known as PCSK1 deficiency or obesity and endocrinopathy due to impaired processing of prohormones, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the function of the hormone-processing enzyme proprotein convertase 1 (PCSK1). People with this condition have severe childhood obesity, hypoadrenalism, hypogonadism, reactive hypoglycemia, and elevated levels of certain prohormones in their blood. It is caused by mutations in the PCSK1 gene on chromosome 5q15. The disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PCSK1 gene.

Van den Ende-Gupta Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by severe contractural arachnodactyly, distinctive facial features, blepharophimosis (abnormal eyelid retraction), and absence of neurological involvement. The syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SCARF2 gene located on chromosome 22q11.21. It is also known as Marden-Walker-like syndrome without psychomotor retardation, VDEGS (Van den Ende-Gupta Syndrome), and blepharophimosis, arachnodactyly, and congenital contractures.

Ankyrin-B syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant heart disease that is characterized by a broad spectrum of cardiac arrhythmias. These arrhythmias can include bradycardia, sinus arrhythmia, delayed conduction/conduction block, idiopathic ventricular fibrillation, and catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia. Ankyrin-B syndrome is caused by mutations in the ANK2 gene on chromosome 4q25-q26. It is related to ankyrin-B related cardiac arrhythmia, which is also a type of autosomal dominant heart disease.

Long QT syndrome 4 (LQT4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by a prolonged QT interval on the electrocardiogram. It is caused by mutations in the ANK2 gene, which is located on chromosome 4q25-q26.

Loose anagen hair syndrome (LHS) is a type of alopecia in which the hair follicles are in the anagen phase, which is the active growth stage. This condition typically affects fair-haired individuals and may present itself during childhood. It can be easily mistaken for other forms of alopecia due to its similar appearance; however, it typically improves with age. The hair can be easily pulled from the scalp without causing any visible damage.
Loose anagen syndrome is another name for loose anagen hair syndrome.

Familial hypertryptophanemia is an amino acid metabolic disorder that is characterized by elevated levels of tryptophan in the urine and plasma. It is caused by mutations in the TDO2 gene, which is located on chromosome 4q32.1. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. It can also be inherited in a compound heterozygous manner, which means that a person has one copy of a normal gene and one copy of a mutated gene.

text: Chromosome 2q37 deletion syndrome is a genetic condition where individuals have a missing or deleted portion of chromosome 2 and the q37 region. This can lead to various physical and developmental issues, such as short stature, brachydactyly (short fingers and toes), mild to moderate intellectual disability, behavioral abnormalities, and dysmorphic facial features. The syndrome is caused by a deletion on the long arm of chromosome 2 at the q37 region, which can be inherited or occur spontaneously.

oculoectodermal syndrome is a type of ectodermal dysplasia characterized by epibulbar dermoids and aplasia cutis congenita, which has a somatic mosaic mutation in the KRAS gene on chromosome 12p12.1. It is also known as Toriello-Lacassie-Droste syndrome and aplasia cutis congenita-epibulbar dermoids syndrome.

Oblique facial clefting 1 (OFC1) is a type of orofacial cleft, which is a congenital defect that occurs when the upper lip and/or palate do not form properly during fetal development. OFC1 is an autosomal dominant disease, meaning that it can be inherited from one parent and passed down through generations. The inheritance of OFC1 involves a mutation in the SPECC1L gene on chromosome 22q11.23. This condition has been classified as Tessier number 4 facial cleft, which refers to a specific type of facial cleft characterized by certain facial features.

Bothnian type palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of non-epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma. It is an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the AQP5 gene on chromosome 12q13.12. The affected areas take on a white, spongy appearance upon exposure to water. It is also known as PPKB and diffuse palmoplantar keratoderma, Bothnian type.

focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma (FNEPPK) is a type of skin condition characterized by localized areas of hyperkeratosis, which are thickened and rough patches on the hands and feet. It primarily affects pressure points and sites of recurrent friction, such as the bottoms of the feet and the palms of the hands. FNEPPK is also known as isolated focal non-epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma (IFNEPPK).

Focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma (FNEPPK1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the development of thick, scaly skin on the palms and soles. It has been linked to mutations in the KRT16 gene located on chromosome 17q21.2. The exact synonym for FNEPPK1 is focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 1.

Focal or diffuse nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the skin and nails. It is characterized by focal or diffuse keratodermas, which are thickened, dry, and scaly areas on the palms and soles of the feet. This condition can also cause plantar blistering and nail changes, but these features may be less severe than in other types of palmoplantar keratoderma. It is caused by mutations in the KRT6C gene on chromosome 12q13.13, which encodes a protein involved in keratinization.

Yes, focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the thickening and hardening of the skin on the palms and soles, often leading to pain and difficulty with gripping objects. The condition is caused by mutations in the TRPV3 gene, which is located on chromosome 17p13.2. It can be passed down through families, and individuals who inherit the mutated gene have a higher risk of developing the disease.
It's important to note that there are different types of keratoderma, and focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 2 is just one of them. It has exact synonym FNEPPK2 which could be used instead of focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 2 in certain contexts.

Kagami Ogata Syndrome, also known as KOS, is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body. It is characterized by polyhydramnios (excessive amniotic fluid), fetal macrosomia (large baby), abdominal wall defects, skeletal abnormalities, feeding difficulties and impaired swallowing, dysmorphic features, developmental delay, and intellectual disability. The syndrome is caused by a heterozygous mutation in an imprinting region on chromosome 14q32.

Temple syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects a person's growth, development and physical appearance. It is caused by a mutation in the PRDM5 gene, which is located on chromosome 14q32. The mutation leads to abnormal regulation of growth hormone production, resulting in short stature, low birth weight, and other characteristic features of the syndrome.

Mulchandani-Bhoj Conlin Syndrome (MBCS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects growth and development. It is characterized by prenatal growth restriction, severe short stature with proportional head circumference, and profound feeding difficulty. MBCS is caused by a heterozygous mutation in an imprinting region on chromosome 20q11-q13. The condition has synonyms such as UPD(20), maternal UPD(20), and maternal uniparental disomy of chromosome 20.

Schaaf Yang Syndrome, also known as MAGEL2-related Prader-Willi-like syndrome (PWLS), is a rare genetic disorder that affects brain development and causes intellectual disability, motor skill delays, and behavioral issues. It is characterized by hypotonia (low muscle tone), small stature, and distinct facial features. The condition is caused by a mutation in the MAGEL2 gene located on chromosome 15q11.2.

Cryptophthalmia is indeed a physical disorder characterized by ocular dysplasia with eyelid malformation. It is also known as cryptophthalmos. If you have any further questions or need more information, feel free to ask!

Isolated cryptophthalmia is a type of cryptophthalmia, which is characterized by the absence of eyelids with skin covering the eye and often an underlying malformed eye. It can be unilateral or bilateral in nature. The term "isolated" means that this condition exists independently and does not have any other associated medical conditions.

I understand that you are providing information about a medical condition called "partial cryptophthalmia." It is an isolated form of cryptophthalmia characterized by an ill-defined upper eyelid that is completely fused, often over an abnormally developed globe and a keratinized cornea. The term used for this condition is "partial cryptophthalmia" or "incomplete cryptophalmos." Please let me know if you have any questions or need further clarification on this topic.

Complete cryptophthalmia is a type of isolated cryptophthalmia. Isolated cryptophthalmia refers to a condition where the eyelids and/or the eyeball itself are absent or abnormal in development, resulting in an eye socket with no visible ocular structures. Complete cryptophthalmia is characterized by the complete absence of both the lid folds and the globe, causing the skin to extend from the brow to the cheek without any identifiable adnexal structures (such as hair follicles or sweat glands). In some cases, a vestigial ocular structure or cyst may be present within the empty socket.
Congenital symblepharon is a rare condition in which the upper eyelid fuses with the eye surface, usually accompanied by microphthalmia. It's classified as an isolated cryptophthalmus.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3, also known as AI3 or hypocalcified amelogenesis imperfecta, is a condition characterized by soft enamel that is initially of normal thickness but lost soon after tooth eruption. This defect in tooth development can lead to an array of problems such as discoloration and chipping of the teeth, sensitivity, and even pain. It is important for individuals with this condition to seek proper dental care and treatment to prevent further complications and maintain a healthy smile.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3c is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by hypocalcified enamel in both the primary and secondary dentition. It has material basis in homozygous mutation in the RELT gene on chromosome 11q13. Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3c is also known as AI3C, amelogenesis imperfecta type IIIC, autosomal recessive amelogenesis imperfecta hypocalcification type.

Jacobsen syndrome, also known as Jacobsen distal 11q deletion syndrome or partial 11q monosomy, is a genetic disorder characterized by growth retardation, psychomotor retardation, distinctive facial features, skeletal abnormalities, and isoimmune thrombocytopenia. It is caused by the deletion of terminal chromosome 11q.

Geleophysic dysplasia, also known as achondroplasia, is a common genetic disorder that affects bone development. It results in short-limb dwarfism, brachydactyly (shortened arms and fingers), characteristic facial appearance, skin thickening, cardiac valvular disease, and laryngotracheal stenosis. Geleophysic dysplasia is caused by a mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene on chromosome 4. It's diagnosed through a combination of physical examination, X-rays, and genetic testing. Treatment options include surgical interventions to correct spinal deformities or other medical conditions associated with the disorder.
Geleophysic dysplasia 1, also known as GPHYSD1, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It has a material basis in mutations in the ADAMTSL2 gene on chromosome 9q34.2.

Gleophysic dysplasia type 2 (GPHYSD2) is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body, including bones and blood vessels. It is an autosomal dominant disease, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it.
Gleophysic dysplasia type 2 occurs when there is a mutation in exon 41 or 42 of the FBN1 gene on chromosome 15q21.1. This gene is responsible for producing fibrillin-1, which is an important protein for the development and maintenance of connective tissue.
There are no specific symptoms associated with GPHYSD2, but it can cause a range of problems related to connective tissue, including high blood pressure in the lungs (pulmonary hypertension), scoliosis, and joint problems. Treatment for GPHYSD2 may include medications to manage symptoms or surgical interventions to correct structural abnormalities.

Geleophysic dysplasia type 3, also known as GPHYSD3, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and cartilage. It is an autosomal dominant condition, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting the disorder if one of their parents passes it on. The LTBP3 gene on chromosome 11q13.1 is responsible for this disorder. There are no specific symptoms associated with GPHYSD3, but it can lead to abnormalities in bone and cartilage development, which may result in short stature, bowed legs, and other skeletal problems.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome (FEPS) is a type of neuropathy characterized by recurrent, stereotyped, episodic intense pain that occurs predominantly in the upper body or lower limbs. The pain is triggered or exacerbated by fatigue, cold exposure, fasting, weather changes and/or physical stress or exertion. It has exact synonym FEPS.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 1, also known as FEPS1, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by onset in infancy of episodic debilitating upper body pain triggered by fasting, cold, and physical stress. The exact cause of this syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TRPA1 gene located on chromosome 8q13.

Familial episodic pain syndrome 2 (FEPS2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by adult-onset paroxysmal pain primarily affecting the distal lower extremities. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SCN10A gene on chromosome 3p22. FEPS2 is also known as Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 2.

That is correct. Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 3, also known as FEPS3, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by early childhood onset of intense episodic pain mainly affecting the distal lower extremities, but sometimes also the upper extremities. The pain cycles can last several days and are exacerbated by fatigue. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene on chromosome 3p22.

Eiken syndrome, also known as Eiken skeletal dysplasia or bone modeling defect of hands and feet, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects bone development. It is characterized by severely delayed ossification primarily of the epiphyses (the ends of long bones), pelvis, hands, and feet. Additionally, there is abnormal bone modeling of the hands and feet. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PTHR1 gene on chromosome 3p21.31.

Pancreatic hypoplasia, diabetes, congenital heart disease syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that the abnormal gene can be passed down from one generation to the next without any genetic recombination.

It is also described as a physical disorder and a syndrome, which are terms used to describe a collection of symptoms or signs that occur together. It has been suggested that this condition has a material basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This means that the condition may have developed during fetal development but was not fully formed.

The exact cause of pancreatic hypoplasia, diabetes, congenital heart disease syndrome is not known, but it has been suggested that it may be caused by a heterozygous mutation in GATA6 on chromosome 18q11.2. This means that there are two copies of the normal gene and one copy of an abnormal gene.

Pancreatic hypoplasia, diabetes, congenital heart disease syndrome has been suggested to have several other exact synonyms, including HDCA, PACHD, Yorifuji-Okuno syndrome, congenital heart defects and other congenital anomalies, congenital pancreatic hypoplasia with diabetes mellitus and congenital heart disease, and pancreatic agenesis and congenital heart defects.

Aminoglycoside-induced deafness is a type of drug-induced hearing loss caused by the use of aminoglycoside antibiotics. This condition has been linked to mutations in certain genes, specifically MTRNR1 and MTCO1 on chromosome 22q13.31, as well as homozygous mutation in TRMU. The exact synonyms for this condition include streptomycin ototoxicity and streptomycin-induced deafness.

x linked deafness 3 is a type of x linked nonsyndromic deafness, which means that it is characterized by hearing loss and not the presence of other physical or developmental abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in a specific region on the X chromosome (Xp21.2) and typically affects males, who experience congenital, bilateral, profound deafness, while females who are heterozygous for the condition may experience milder hearing loss at higher frequencies later in life.

text: X-linked deafness 2, also known as Nance deafness or DFN3, is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive conductive and sensorineural hearing loss and pathognomonic inner ear anomalies. It has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the POU3F4 gene or upstream regulatory elements of this gene on chromosome Xq21.1. The condition is also known by other synonyms such as DFNX2, X-linked deafness type 2, X-linked mixed conductive and neurosensory deafness, X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural hearing loss, X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural deafness, X-linked sensorineural deafness, X-linked stapes gusher syndrome, conductive deafness 3 with stapes fixation, or mixed deafness with perilymphatic gusher.

X-linked deafness 7, also known as DFNX7 and X-linked external auditory canal atresia-dilated internal auditory canal-facial dysmorphism syndrome, is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by congenital, bilateral, mixed or conductive hearing loss and other ear anomalies that have a material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutation in the GPRASP2 gene on chromosome Xq22.1.

x linked deafness 1 is a type of x linked nonsyndromic deafness.
x linked deafness 1 has definition An X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by congenital profound sensorineural hearing loss in males and mild to moderate high-frequency hearing loss in heterozygous females that has_material_basis_in mutation in the PRPS1 gene on chromosome Xq22.3..
x linked deafness 1 has exact synonym DFN2.
x linked deafness 1 has exact synonym DFNX1.

X-linked deafness 6, also known as DFNX6, is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic hearing loss. It is characterized by severe bilateral sensorineural hearing loss with cochlear malformation in males and mild to moderate hearing loss in females with later onset. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the COL4A6 gene on chromosome Xq22.3.

X-linked deafness 5 (DFNX5) is a type of X-linked recessive disorder that affects the auditory and sensory nerves. It is characterized by childhood onset of auditory neuropathy, which leads to later onset of distal sensory impairment due to diffuse peripheral neuropathy. This condition has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the AIFM1 gene located on chromosome Xq26.1. The exact synonyms for DFNX5 include AUNX1, X-linked HSAN with deafness, and X-linked auditory neuropathy 1 with peripheral sensory neuropathy.

Cerebellar ataxia type 42 (SCA42) is an autosomal dominant genetic disorder characterized by a group of symptoms affecting balance, coordination, and speech. These symptoms typically develop slowly over time, with the age of onset ranging from early adulthood to late middle age. SCA42 is caused by mutations in the CACNA1G gene located on chromosome 17q21. The condition has a slow progression and can lead to severe disability if left untreated.

Cerebellar ataxia type 47, also known as SCA47, is a form of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that affects adults and sometimes children. It is characterized by slowly progressive cerebellar ataxia or in some cases, earlier onset with delayed motor development and short stature. The condition results from mutations in the PUM1 gene located on chromosome 1p35.2.
Cerebellar ataxia type 41, also known as SCA41, is an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the TRPC3 gene on chromosome 4q27.

Cerebellar ataxia type 43, also known as spinocerebellar atrophy type 43 (SCA43), is a genetic disorder characterized by adult-onset, slowly progressive gait and limb ataxia. It often accompanies peripheral neuropathy and affects the motor system. The condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the MME gene located on chromosome 3q25.2.

cerebellar ataxia type 48, also known as SCA48, is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by mid-adult onset of gait ataxia and/or cognitive-affective symptoms. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the STUB1 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3.<|end_of_text|>

The cerebellar ataxia type 9, also known as SCA9, is a form of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that causes adult onset of symptoms such as ataxia and imbalance. It is characterized by the presence of demyelinating lesions on brain MRI.

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency, mitochondrial type 1, also known as MC5DM1, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by lactic acidosis, hypotonia, and neurodegenerative symptoms. It is caused by mutations in the MTATP6 gene located on the mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA). This condition leads to the dysfunction of complex V, which plays a crucial role in ATP production within the mitochondria. As a result, affected individuals may experience various symptoms such as muscle weakness, seizures, and developmental delays. Early onset and progressive nature of this disorder make it essential for those affected to receive proper medical care and support.

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency, nuclear type 6 is a type of mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency characterized by episodic regression of gross motor skills beginning in early childhood that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATP5MD gene on chromosome 10q24.33. It is also known as MC5DN6.

Adult-onset ataxia and polyneuropathy is indeed a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, characterized by adult-onset symptoms of ataxia (loss of coordination) and polyneuropathy (nerve damage in multiple areas). This condition has a material basis in heteroplasmic mutation in the mitochondrial gene MTATP6.

That is correct. Mitochondrial nonsyndromic sensorineural deafness (MSSND) refers to a type of hearing loss that results from mutations in specific mitochondrial genes, including MTRNR1, MTTS1, MTCO1, MTTH, MTND1 and MTTI. These genes are responsible for the functioning of mitochondria, which play a crucial role in energy production within cells. When these genes are mutated, it can lead to defects or dysfunction in the mitochondria, resulting in hearing loss.

Autosomal mitochondrial sensorineural deafness is a type of digenic disease, which means it's caused by the combination of two genes. It is characterized by progressive, severe to profound deafness that has a material basis in digenic inheritance of mutations in the mitochondrial gene MTRNR1 and an unidentified nuclear gene.

Infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a type of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that occurs primarily in children and young adults. It is characterized by an enlarged heart, thickening of the heart muscle, and congestive heart failure. This condition has been linked to mutations in the genes MTATP6 and MTATP8, which are involved in mitochondrial function.

Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy (LHON) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the optic nerve, leading to progressive vision loss. It is caused by mutations in one of four mitochondrial DNA genes: MT-ATP6, MT-CO1, MT-CYB, or MT-ND1. LHON primarily affects men and is more common among individuals of Ashkenazi Jewish descent.
LHON typically presents with acute vision loss in one eye, which may be accompanied by pain, redness, and swelling of the affected eye. If left untreated, additional vision loss can occur over time. Diagnosis requires a combination of clinical examination, genetic testing, and imaging studies such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) or optical coherence tomography (OCT). Treatment options for LHON include supportive care, antioxidant therapy, and gene replacement therapy. Gene replacement therapy involves the introduction of a healthy copy of the faulty mitochondrial DNA gene into the patient's cells using viral vectors. This approach has shown promise in clinical trials for slowing or halting vision loss in LHON patients.

Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and dystonia is a type of Leber plus disease, which is characterized by Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and dystonia. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the mitochondrial genes MTND6, MTND4, MTND1 or MTND3 that make up the mitochondrial complex I. It is also known by its exact synonyms LDYT, Leber optic atrophy and dystonia, Leber optic atrophy with dystonia, Marsden syndrome, and familial dystonia with visual failure and striatal lucencies.

Leber hereditary optic neuropathy with demyelinating disease of the CNS is a type of Leber plus disease.
Leber hereditary optic neuropathy with demyelinating disease of the CNS has the definition A Leber plus disease characterized by Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and demyelination in the central nervous system.

Y-linked deafness, also known as DFNY (Deafness, Fanconi Syndrome, Nephropathy and Y-Linked), is a type of non-syndromic deafness caused by mutations in the SLC26A4 gene on the Y chromosome. It is inherited through the paternal line and can affect both males and females. The condition is characterized by progressive hearing loss, starting in childhood or adolescence, and can lead to complete deafness by adulthood if left untreated.

Y-linked deafness 2, also known as DFNY2, is a type of Y-linked hearing loss. It affects males and typically presents with bilateral progressive sensorineural hearing loss starting in the third to fifth decades of life. The condition has a material basis due to mutations in the TBL1Y gene located on chromosome Yp11.2.

Y-linked deafness 1, also known as DFNY1, is a type of Y-linked deafness. It is characterized by male-limited postlingual progressive sensorineural hearing loss of variable severity, with onset in the first to third decades of life.

46, XX sex reversal is a type of gonadal dysgenesis characterized by the presence of an XY karyotype and female external genitalia ranging from normal to ambiguous. It is also known as 46,XX testicular DSD or De la Chapelle syndrome.

46 XX sex reversal 1 is a genetic condition where the individual has one X and one Y chromosome. This results in the appearance of male characteristics, such as a deep voice and beard growth, but the individual has female reproductive organs. It's caused by a chromosomal translocation that moves the SRY gene from the Y chromosome to the X chromosome.

46, XX sex reversal type 3 (SRXXX3) is a genetic condition that occurs due to an abnormality in the SOX3 gene on the X chromosome. This condition affects the development of sexual characteristics and can result in atypical genitalia, such as a hypospadias or clitoral enlargement in males, and/or vaginal agenesis or labial fusion in females. It is considered as one of the types of 46, XX sex reversal.

46, XX sex reversal 2 (SRXX2) is a genetic disorder that affects sexual development in individuals with the condition. It occurs when there is an increase or duplication of a specific region on chromosome 17q24. This genetic anomaly can lead to various issues related to sexual development, including ambiguous genitalia, virilization (masculinization) in females, and feminization (hypoandrogenism) in males.

SRXX2 is a form of autosomal dominant inheritance, which means that if one parent has the gene for it, there is a 50% chance that their offspring will inherit the condition. However, not all individuals with the gene will develop the disorder or experience its full range of symptoms.

To diagnose SRXX2, healthcare professionals may perform physical exams, genetic testing to determine chromosome structure and function, and endocrine evaluations to assess hormone levels. Treatment options for SRXX2 depend on the severity of the condition but can include medical interventions such as hormone replacement therapy or surgery to address specific issues related to sexual development.

In summary, 46, XX sex reversal 2 is a genetic disorder caused by an increase or duplication of a specific region on chromosome 17q24. It affects sexual development and can lead to various physical characteristics, including ambiguous genitalia, virilization in females, and feminization in males.

46, XX sex reversal 4 (also known as SRXX4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It occurs when there is a mutation in the NR5A1 gene on chromosome 9q33.3. This genetic abnormality results in the development of male characteristics, such as an enlarged clitoris and underdeveloped penis, in affected females. The condition can also affect the internal sex organs and secondary sexual characteristics. It is important to note that this disease has a strong genetic basis and can be inherited from one or both parents if they are carriers of the mutated gene.

X-linked cardiac valvular dysplasia (XMVD) is a type of heart valve disease that occurs due to mutations in the FLNA gene on the X chromosome. It is characterized by multivalvular dysplasia and regurgitation, with more severe symptoms in hemizygous males compared to heterozygous females. The condition has a material basis in inheritance and can lead to Ehlers-Danlos syndrome type 5 (EDS 5) when present.

X-linked VATER (VACTERL) association is a type of genetic disorder that affects various organ systems in the body, primarily due to the presence of mutations on the X chromosome. It is characterized by the combination of four main congenital anomalies:

1. Vertebral anomalies (V) - abnormal formation or development of vertebrae in the spine.
2. Anal atresia (A) - absence or underdevelopment of the anus and rectum.
3. Tracheoesophageal fistula (TEF) - an abnormal connection between the trachea and esophagus, which can lead to aspiration and infection.
4. Renal anomalies (R) - abnormalities in the formation or function of the kidneys.

X-linked VATER association is inherited in an X-linked recessive manner, which means that a male with this condition has one copy of the mutated gene (XY0), while a female with the condition has two copies of the mutated gene (XX0). Females who have only one copy of the mutated gene (X0) are usually carriers and can pass the gene on to their offspring.

The severity of X-linked VATER association varies depending on the specific genetic mutations present, but it can lead to a range of health problems, including respiratory distress, feeding difficulties, kidney issues, and hydrocephalus (in some cases). Treatment may involve surgery, medication, and other medical interventions to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

x linked thrombocytopenia with beta thalassemia is a type of hematopoietic system disease characterized by variable thrombocytopenia, hemolytic anemia, splenomegaly, and abnormalities in hemoglobin chain synthesis resulting from imbalance between the alpha and beta chains that has a material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutation of the DNA binding domain of the GATA1 gene on chromosome Xp11.23. This condition is also known by several other names, such as GATA1-related X-linked cytopenia, XLTT, beta-thalassemia-X-linked thrombocytopenia syndrome, and thrombocytopenia, platelet dysfunction, hemolysis, and imbalanced globin synthesis.

X-linked properdin deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that occurs due to the absence or malfunction of the protein properdin. Properdin plays an essential role in the activation of the complement system, which helps neutralize pathogens and remove damaged cells from the body. When there is a deficiency of properdin, individuals with X-linked properdin deficiency are more susceptible to infections caused by Neisseria bacteria, particularly those that produce lipopolysaccharide (LPS). These infections can cause severe inflammation and sepsis. X-linked properdin deficiency is inherited in an X-linked recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

46 XY sex reversal 6, also known as 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, MAP3K1-related, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of sexual organs in an individual. It is characterized by having an XY chromosome (46,XY), female-typical genitalia, and failure to develop secondary sex characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition has been linked to a mutation in the MAP3K1 gene located on chromosome 5q11.2. It is considered an autosomal dominant disorder, meaning that it can be passed down through family genetics.

46 XY sex reversal 9, also known as ZFPM2-related 46 XY sex reversal or SRXY9, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ZFPM2 gene on chromosome 8q23.1.

46 XY sex reversal 4, also known as 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, with 9p24.3 deletion, is a chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty including menstruation but without the presence of other features associated with the chromosome 9p deletion syndrome. It has a material basis in a heterozygous deletion of a region on chromosome 9p.

46 XY sex reversal 3, also known as NR5A1-related disorder of sex development, is a genetic condition in which an individual with a typical male (XY) chromosome pattern has female genitalia and other sexual characteristics. This can lead to failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. The condition is caused by mutations in the NR5A1 gene on chromosome 9q33.3.

This is a genetic disorder that occurs due to mutations in the AKR1C2 gene on chromosome 10p15.1. It affects the development of sex organs and causes individuals with this condition to be born with female-like genitalia but have a Y chromosome, resulting in a combination of male and female biological characteristics. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

46 XY sex reversal, also known as 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis or partial androgen insensitivity syndrome (PAIS), is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of one X and one Y chromosome in an individual's cells. This condition can result in a variety of developmental abnormalities, particularly related to reproductive organs and secondary sex characteristics.

46 XY sex reversal occurs when a person with normally developing male gonads (testes) has genetic factors that cause them to develop female reproductive organs (ovaries). This can lead to a combination of features typically associated with both male and female anatomy, such as the presence of ovarian tissue in addition to testicular tissue.

46 XY sex reversal is considered to be one form of Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (AIS), which affects individuals who are genetically male but have a partial or complete resistance to androgens, the hormones responsible for typical male development. In some cases, 46 XY sex reversal may also be accompanied by other genetic disorders or chromosomal abnormalities that can contribute to its development.

It is important to note that while 46 XY sex reversal is not a rare condition (with an estimated prevalence of 1 in every 2,000 to 3,000 male births), it may be underdiagnosed due to a lack of awareness and understanding of the condition. Proper diagnosis typically involves a combination of genetic testing, physical examination, and hormone analysis. Treatment options for individuals with 46 XY sex reversal can vary widely depending on their specific needs and goals, but may include hormone replacement therapy, gender-affirming surgeries, and psychological support to address issues related to self-esteem and body image.

46 XY sex reversal 10, also known as chromosome 17q24 deletion syndrome, is a genetic condition that affects an individual's sexual development. It occurs due to the deletion of a region upstream of the SOX9 gene on chromosome 17q24, which leads to the absence or underdevelopment of male sex organs and the development of female-typical genitalia. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that one copy of the gene is sufficient for the individual to develop the condition. Individuals with 46 XY sex reversal 10 may also experience delayed or absent puberty, and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics, such as breasts and long hair.

The 46,XY sex reversal, also known as Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (AIS), is a genetic disorder where an individual with the typical male XY chromosome pattern (46,XY) develops female reproductive organs and other characteristics that are typically associated with the female sex. The condition occurs due to a defect in the development of the fetal gonads, which can result from genetic or environmental factors.

AIS is characterized by the presence of male genitalia (e.g., a penis) at birth, but the individual may have internal female reproductive organs such as ovaries, uterus, and fallopian tubes. AIS can affect an individual's hormonal balance, causing issues with puberty, growth, and development.

Treatment for 46,XY sex reversal depends on the severity of the condition and the affected individual's overall health. In some cases, medical intervention may be necessary to induce female puberty or suppress male puberty if it has already begun. Additionally, hormone replacement therapy may be recommended to address any imbalances caused by the disorder.

It is important for individuals with 46,XY sex reversal to work closely with healthcare professionals to manage their condition effectively and ensure a healthy life.

46 XY sex reversal, also known as 46,XY sex reversal 2 or DSS, is a genetic condition that affects the development of sexual characteristics in individuals. It occurs when there is a duplication of the NR0B1 gene on chromosome Xp21.2, resulting in an XY karyotype and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition is typically characterized by phenotypically female genitalia. While it can be caused by a variety of factors, including exposure to certain chemicals during pregnancy or birth defects, the exact cause in each individual is often not known. Treatment options depend on the underlying cause and may include hormone replacement therapy, surgery, and psychological support.

46 XY sex reversal, also known as 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, is a genetic condition in which an individual with the typical male (XY) chromosome configuration has female reproductive organs and other features associated with the female sex.
46 XY sex reversal occurs when there is a defect in the development of the reproductive organs due to abnormalities in the SRY gene on the Y-chromosome. The condition typically affects male infants during fetal development, but it can also occur later in life.
46 XY sex reversal can be diagnosed through chromosome analysis and genetic testing. Treatment may involve hormone replacement therapy to induce the development of female reproductive organs or other interventions depending on the individual's specific needs.

x linked panhypopituitarism is a form of pituitary dwarfism that results from a genetic mutation on the X chromosome. It is one of several types of panhypopituitarism, which refers to a group of disorders involving the underproduction or absence of one or more hormones produced by the pituitary gland. X linked panhypopituitarism specifically has a material basis in duplications in the SOX3 gene on chromosome Xq27.1, and is also known as PHPX or pituitary dwarfism IV.

TARPS, or Tarp Syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects many different organ systems in the body. It is characterized by several distinctive features, including talipes equinovarus (clubfoot), atrial septal defect (a hole in the heart), Robin sequence (micrognathia, cleft palate, and glossoptosis), and persistent left superior vena cava. These abnormalities often lead to late prenatal or early postnatal mortality. The disorder is caused by a hemizygous mutation in the RBM10 gene on chromosome Xp11.3, which provides material basis for the syndrome.
TARPS is also known as Pierre Robin sequence-congenital heart defect-talipes syndrome, Pierre Robin syndrome-congenital heart defect-talipes syndrome, or simply TARPS. It is important to note that this disorder can be misdiagnosed due to the overlapping symptoms with other genetic disorders. If you suspect that you or a loved one may have TARPS, it is crucial to consult with a medical professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Waisman syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by delayed psychomotor development, impaired intellectual development, and early-onset Parkinson disease. It has material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the RAB39B gene on chromosome Xq28. The disorder is also known as Laxova-Opitz syndrome and early-onset parkinsonism-intellectual disability syndrome.

Otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder, also known as OPD spectrum disorder or OPSD, is a type of bone development disease that affects the growth and development of long bones in the body. It is characterized by facial anomalies and a generalized bone dysplasia with osteodysplastic changes, leading to skeletal dysplasia in varying combinations and degrees of undertubulation of the long bones, cortical irregularity, and campomelia.

It is important to note that not all subtypes of OPD spectrum disorder are associated with mutations in FLNA on chromosome Xq28. While this is a common genetic cause for some cases of OPD, it's not the only one. This condition can also result from other genetic or environmental factors.

OPD spectrum disorder is also known as fronto-otopalatodigital osteodysplasia, which emphasizes its specific involvement of the frontal and occipital bones in addition to the mandible.

Otopalatodigital syndrome type 1 is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the hands, feet, and face. It is caused by mutations in the FLNA gene on the X chromosome. The symptoms include cleft palate, mild skeletal anomalies, and conductive deafness. It is also known as OPD I syndrome, Taybi syndrome, and oto-palato-digital syndrome type 1.

Otopalatodigital syndrome type 2 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the hand and foot, as well as the face. It is characterized by severe skeletal abnormalities, including malformations in the hindbrain, heart, intestines, and kidneys. These malformations can lead to perinatal death in males or less severe symptoms in females. The disorder is inherited in an X-linked dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the defective gene on the X chromosome is sufficient to cause the condition. It has been given several other names, including Andre syndrome, OPD II syndrome, and OPD syndrome 2.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia (FMD) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bone and cartilage in the skull, face, and limbs. It is characterized by abnormal ossification and skeletal patterning of the axial and appendicular skeleton, facial dysmorphism, urogenital anomalies, and hearing loss. The disorder is caused by mutations in the Fibroblast growth factor receptor 1 (FGFR1) gene, which plays a critical role in bone development. FMD typically presents in early childhood with severe symptoms that can affect the individual's overall health and quality of life. There is no cure for the disorder, but treatment options may include medications to manage pain and other symptoms, as well as surgical interventions to correct or alleviate complications such as hydrocephalus or spinal abnormalities.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia 1 is a type of frontometaphyseal dysplasia characterized by generalized skeletal dysplasia, deafness, and urogenital defects that has material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutation in FLNA on chromosome Xq28.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia 2, also known as FMD2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by skeletal dysplasia, deafness, urogenital defects and an increased tendency to form keloid scars due to a heterozygous mutation in MAP3K7 on chromosome 6q15.

melnick needles syndrome is a type of x linked monogenic disease that is characterized by short stature, facial dysmorphism, osseous abnormalities involving the majority of the axial and appendicular skeleton resulting in impaired speech and masticatory problems. It has a material basis in heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in the FLNA gene on chromosome Xq28. It is also known as MNS, Melnick-Needles osteodysplasty, and osteodysplasty of Melnick and Needles.

Frank ter Haar syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body. It is caused by mutations in the SH3PXD2B gene, which is located on chromosome 5q35.1.
